  74 # BOM character (byte order mark)
  75 # This exists at the beginning of a file to indicate endianness
  76 # of a file (stream). Unfortunately, this marker screws up parsing,
  77 # so we need to remove it if we see it.
  78 _BOM = "\ufeff"

  80 _doc_read_csv_and_table = (
  81     r"""
  82 {summary}
  83 
  84 Also supports optionally iterating or breaking of the file
  85 into chunks.
  86 
  87 Additional help can be found in the online docs for
  88 `IO Tools <https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/user_guide/io.html>`_.
  89 
  90 Parameters
  91 ----------
  92 filepath_or_buffer : str, path object or file-like object
  93     Any valid string path is acceptable. The string could be a URL. Valid
  94     URL schemes include http, ftp, s3, gs, and file. For file URLs, a host is
  95     expected. A local file could be: file://localhost/path/to/table.csv.
  96 
  97     If you want to pass in a path object, pandas accepts any ``os.PathLike``.
  98 
  99     By file-like object, we refer to objects with a ``read()`` method, such as
 100     a file handler (e.g. via builtin ``open`` function) or ``StringIO``.
 101 sep : str, default {_default_sep}
 102     Delimiter to use. If sep is None, the C engine cannot automatically detect
 103     the separator, but the Python parsing engine can, meaning the latter will
 104     be used and automatically detect the separator by Python's builtin sniffer
 105     tool, ``csv.Sniffer``. In addition, separators longer than 1 character and
 106     different from ``'\s+'`` will be interpreted as regular expressions and
 107     will also force the use of the Python parsing engine. Note that regex
 108     delimiters are prone to ignoring quoted data. Regex example: ``'\r\t'``.
 109 delimiter : str, default ``None``
 110     Alias for sep.
 111 header : int, list of int, default 'infer'
 112     Row number(s) to use as the column names, and the start of the
 113     data.  Default behavior is to infer the column names: if no names
 114     are passed the behavior is identical to ``header=0`` and column
 115     names are inferred from the first line of the file, if column
 116     names are passed explicitly then the behavior is identical to
 117     ``header=None``. Explicitly pass ``header=0`` to be able to
 118     replace existing names. The header can be a list of integers that
 119     specify row locations for a multi-index on the columns
 120     e.g. [0,1,3]. Intervening rows that are not specified will be
 121     skipped (e.g. 2 in this example is skipped). Note that this
 122     parameter ignores commented lines and empty lines if
 123     ``skip_blank_lines=True``, so ``header=0`` denotes the first line of
 124     data rather than the first line of the file.
 125 names : array-like, optional
 126     List of column names to use. If the file contains a header row,
 127     then you should explicitly pass ``header=0`` to override the column names.
 128     Duplicates in this list are not allowed.
 129 index_col : int, str, sequence of int / str, or False, default ``None``
 130   Column(s) to use as the row labels of the ``DataFrame``, either given as
 131   string name or column index. If a sequence of int / str is given, a
 132   MultiIndex is used.
 133 
 134   Note: ``index_col=False`` can be used to force pandas to *not* use the first
 135   column as the index, e.g. when you have a malformed file with delimiters at
 136   the end of each line.
 137 usecols : list-like or callable, optional
 138     Return a subset of the columns. If list-like, all elements must either
 139     be positional (i.e. integer indices into the document columns) or strings
 140     that correspond to column names provided either by the user in `names` or
 141     inferred from the document header row(s). For example, a valid list-like
 142     `usecols` parameter would be ``[0, 1, 2]`` or ``['foo', 'bar', 'baz']``.
 143     Element order is ignored, so ``usecols=[0, 1]`` is the same as ``[1, 0]``.
 144     To instantiate a DataFrame from ``data`` with element order preserved use
 145     ``pd.read_csv(data, usecols=['foo', 'bar'])[['foo', 'bar']]`` for columns
 146     in ``['foo', 'bar']`` order or
 147     ``pd.read_csv(data, usecols=['foo', 'bar'])[['bar', 'foo']]``
 148     for ``['bar', 'foo']`` order.
 149 
 150     If callable, the callable function will be evaluated against the column
 151     names, returning names where the callable function evaluates to True. An
 152     example of a valid callable argument would be ``lambda x: x.upper() in
 153     ['AAA', 'BBB', 'DDD']``. Using this parameter results in much faster
 154     parsing time and lower memory usage.
 155 squeeze : bool, default False
 156     If the parsed data only contains one column then return a Series.
 157 prefix : str, optional
 158     Prefix to add to column numbers when no header, e.g. 'X' for X0, X1, ...
 159 mangle_dupe_cols : bool, default True
 160     Duplicate columns will be specified as 'X', 'X.1', ...'X.N', rather than
 161     'X'...'X'. Passing in False will cause data to be overwritten if there
 162     are duplicate names in the columns.
 163 dtype : Type name or dict of column -> type, optional
 164     Data type for data or columns. E.g. {{'a': np.float64, 'b': np.int32,
 165     'c': 'Int64'}}
 166     Use `str` or `object` together with suitable `na_values` settings
 167     to preserve and not interpret dtype.
 168     If converters are specified, they will be applied INSTEAD
 169     of dtype conversion.
 170 engine : {{'c', 'python'}}, optional
 171     Parser engine to use. The C engine is faster while the python engine is
 172     currently more feature-complete.
 173 converters : dict, optional
 174     Dict of functions for converting values in certain columns. Keys can either
 175     be integers or column labels.
 176 true_values : list, optional
 177     Values to consider as True.
 178 false_values : list, optional
 179     Values to consider as False.
 180 skipinitialspace : bool, default False
 181     Skip spaces after delimiter.
 182 skiprows : list-like, int or callable, optional
 183     Line numbers to skip (0-indexed) or number of lines to skip (int)
 184     at the start of the file.
 185 
 186     If callable, the callable function will be evaluated against the row
 187     indices, returning True if the row should be skipped and False otherwise.
 188     An example of a valid callable argument would be ``lambda x: x in [0, 2]``.
 189 skipfooter : int, default 0
 190     Number of lines at bottom of file to skip (Unsupported with engine='c').
 191 nrows : int, optional
 192     Number of rows of file to read. Useful for reading pieces of large files.
 193 na_values : scalar, str, list-like, or dict, optional
 194     Additional strings to recognize as NA/NaN. If dict passed, specific
 195     per-column NA values.  By default the following values are interpreted as
 196     NaN: '"""
 197     + fill("', '".join(sorted(STR_NA_VALUES)), 70, subsequent_indent="    ")
 198     + """'.
 199 keep_default_na : bool, default True
 200     Whether or not to include the default NaN values when parsing the data.
 201     Depending on whether `na_values` is passed in, the behavior is as follows:
 202 
 203     * If `keep_default_na` is True, and `na_values` are specified, `na_values`
 204       is appended to the default NaN values used for parsing.
 205     * If `keep_default_na` is True, and `na_values` are not specified, only
 206       the default NaN values are used for parsing.
 207     * If `keep_default_na` is False, and `na_values` are specified, only
 208       the NaN values specified `na_values` are used for parsing.
 209     * If `keep_default_na` is False, and `na_values` are not specified, no
 210       strings will be parsed as NaN.
 211 
 212     Note that if `na_filter` is passed in as False, the `keep_default_na` and
 213     `na_values` parameters will be ignored.
 214 na_filter : bool, default True
 215     Detect missing value markers (empty strings and the value of na_values). In
 216     data without any NAs, passing na_filter=False can improve the performance
 217     of reading a large file.
 218 verbose : bool, default False
 219     Indicate number of NA values placed in non-numeric columns.
 220 skip_blank_lines : bool, default True
 221     If True, skip over blank lines rather than interpreting as NaN values.
 222 parse_dates : bool or list of int or names or list of lists or dict, \
 223 default False
 224     The behavior is as follows:
 225 
 226     * boolean. If True -> try parsing the index.
 227     * list of int or names. e.g. If [1, 2, 3] -> try parsing columns 1, 2, 3
 228       each as a separate date column.
 229     * list of lists. e.g.  If [[1, 3]] -> combine columns 1 and 3 and parse as
 230       a single date column.
 231     * dict, e.g. {{'foo' : [1, 3]}} -> parse columns 1, 3 as date and call
 232       result 'foo'
 233 
 234     If a column or index cannot be represented as an array of datetimes,
 235     say because of an unparseable value or a mixture of timezones, the column
 236     or index will be returned unaltered as an object data type. For
 237     non-standard datetime parsing, use ``pd.to_datetime`` after
 238     ``pd.read_csv``. To parse an index or column with a mixture of timezones,
 239     specify ``date_parser`` to be a partially-applied
 240     :func:`pandas.to_datetime` with ``utc=True``. See
 241     :ref:`io.csv.mixed_timezones` for more.
 242 
 243     Note: A fast-path exists for iso8601-formatted dates.
 244 infer_datetime_format : bool, default False
 245     If True and `parse_dates` is enabled, pandas will attempt to infer the
 246     format of the datetime strings in the columns, and if it can be inferred,
 247     switch to a faster method of parsing them. In some cases this can increase
 248     the parsing speed by 5-10x.
 249 keep_date_col : bool, default False
 250     If True and `parse_dates` specifies combining multiple columns then
 251     keep the original columns.
 252 date_parser : function, optional
 253     Function to use for converting a sequence of string columns to an array of
 254     datetime instances. The default uses ``dateutil.parser.parser`` to do the
 255     conversion. Pandas will try to call `date_parser` in three different ways,
 256     advancing to the next if an exception occurs: 1) Pass one or more arrays
 257     (as defined by `parse_dates`) as arguments; 2) concatenate (row-wise) the
 258     string values from the columns defined by `parse_dates` into a single array
 259     and pass that; and 3) call `date_parser` once for each row using one or
 260     more strings (corresponding to the columns defined by `parse_dates`) as
 261     arguments.
 262 dayfirst : bool, default False
 263     DD/MM format dates, international and European format.
 264 cache_dates : bool, default True
 265     If True, use a cache of unique, converted dates to apply the datetime
 266     conversion. May produce significant speed-up when parsing duplicate
 267     date strings, especially ones with timezone offsets.
 268 
 269     .. versionadded:: 0.25.0
 270 iterator : bool, default False
 271     Return TextFileReader object for iteration or getting chunks with
 272     ``get_chunk()``.
 273 chunksize : int, optional
 274     Return TextFileReader object for iteration.
 275     See the `IO Tools docs
 276     <https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/io.html#io-chunking>`_
 277     for more information on ``iterator`` and ``chunksize``.
 278 compression : {{'infer', 'gzip', 'bz2', 'zip', 'xz', None}}, default 'infer'
 279     For on-the-fly decompression of on-disk data. If 'infer' and
 280     `filepath_or_buffer` is path-like, then detect compression from the
 281     following extensions: '.gz', '.bz2', '.zip', or '.xz' (otherwise no
 282     decompression). If using 'zip', the ZIP file must contain only one data
 283     file to be read in. Set to None for no decompression.
 284 thousands : str, optional
 285     Thousands separator.
 286 decimal : str, default '.'
 287     Character to recognize as decimal point (e.g. use ',' for European data).
 288 lineterminator : str (length 1), optional
 289     Character to break file into lines. Only valid with C parser.
 290 quotechar : str (length 1), optional
 291     The character used to denote the start and end of a quoted item. Quoted
 292     items can include the delimiter and it will be ignored.
 293 quoting : int or csv.QUOTE_* instance, default 0
 294     Control field quoting behavior per ``csv.QUOTE_*`` constants. Use one of
 295     QUOTE_MINIMAL (0), QUOTE_ALL (1), QUOTE_NONNUMERIC (2) or QUOTE_NONE (3).
 296 doublequote : bool, default ``True``
 297    When quotechar is specified and quoting is not ``QUOTE_NONE``, indicate
 298    whether or not to interpret two consecutive quotechar elements INSIDE a
 299    field as a single ``quotechar`` element.
 300 escapechar : str (length 1), optional
 301     One-character string used to escape other characters.
 302 comment : str, optional
 303     Indicates remainder of line should not be parsed. If found at the beginning
 304     of a line, the line will be ignored altogether. This parameter must be a
 305     single character. Like empty lines (as long as ``skip_blank_lines=True``),
 306     fully commented lines are ignored by the parameter `header` but not by
 307     `skiprows`. For example, if ``comment='#'``, parsing
 308     ``#empty\\na,b,c\\n1,2,3`` with ``header=0`` will result in 'a,b,c' being
 309     treated as the header.
 310 encoding : str, optional
 311     Encoding to use for UTF when reading/writing (ex. 'utf-8'). `List of Python
 312     standard encodings
 313     <https://docs.python.org/3/library/codecs.html#standard-encodings>`_ .
 314 dialect : str or csv.Dialect, optional
 315     If provided, this parameter will override values (default or not) for the
 316     following parameters: `delimiter`, `doublequote`, `escapechar`,
 317     `skipinitialspace`, `quotechar`, and `quoting`. If it is necessary to
 318     override values, a ParserWarning will be issued. See csv.Dialect
 319     documentation for more details.
 320 error_bad_lines : bool, default True
 321     Lines with too many fields (e.g. a csv line with too many commas) will by
 322     default cause an exception to be raised, and no DataFrame will be returned.
 323     If False, then these "bad lines" will dropped from the DataFrame that is
 324     returned.
 325 warn_bad_lines : bool, default True
 326     If error_bad_lines is False, and warn_bad_lines is True, a warning for each
 327     "bad line" will be output.
 328 delim_whitespace : bool, default False
 329     Specifies whether or not whitespace (e.g. ``' '`` or ``'\t'``) will be
 330     used as the sep. Equivalent to setting ``sep='\\s+'``. If this option
 331     is set to True, nothing should be passed in for the ``delimiter``
 332     parameter.
 333 low_memory : bool, default True
 334     Internally process the file in chunks, resulting in lower memory use
 335     while parsing, but possibly mixed type inference.  To ensure no mixed
 336     types either set False, or specify the type with the `dtype` parameter.
 337     Note that the entire file is read into a single DataFrame regardless,
 338     use the `chunksize` or `iterator` parameter to return the data in chunks.
 339     (Only valid with C parser).
 340 memory_map : bool, default False
 341     If a filepath is provided for `filepath_or_buffer`, map the file object
 342     directly onto memory and access the data directly from there. Using this
 343     option can improve performance because there is no longer any I/O overhead.
 344 float_precision : str, optional
 345     Specifies which converter the C engine should use for floating-point
 346     values. The options are `None` for the ordinary converter,
 347     `high` for the high-precision converter, and `round_trip` for the
 348     round-trip converter.
 349 
 350 Returns
 351 -------
 352 DataFrame or TextParser
 353     A comma-separated values (csv) file is returned as two-dimensional
 354     data structure with labeled axes.
 355 
 356 See Also
 357 --------
 358 DataFrame.to_csv : Write DataFrame to a comma-separated values (csv) file.
 359 read_csv : Read a comma-separated values (csv) file into DataFrame.
 360 read_fwf : Read a table of fixed-width formatted lines into DataFrame.
 361 
 362 Examples
 363 --------
 364 >>> pd.{func_name}('data.csv')  # doctest: +SKIP
 365 """
 366 )

 369 def _validate_integer(name, val, min_val=0):
 370     """
 371     Checks whether the 'name' parameter for parsing is either
 372     an integer OR float that can SAFELY be cast to an integer
 373     without losing accuracy. Raises a ValueError if that is
 374     not the case.
 375 
 376     Parameters
 377     ----------
 378     name : string
 379         Parameter name (used for error reporting)
 380     val : int or float
 381         The value to check
 382     min_val : int
 383         Minimum allowed value (val < min_val will result in a ValueError)
 384     """
 385     msg = f"'{name:s}' must be an integer >={min_val:d}"
 386 
 387     if val is not None:
 388         if is_float(val):
 389             if int(val) != val:
 390                 raise ValueError(msg)
 391             val = int(val)
 392         elif not (is_integer(val) and val >= min_val):
 393             raise ValueError(msg)
 394 
 395     return val
 396 
 397 
 398 def _validate_names(names):
 399     """
 400     Raise ValueError if the `names` parameter contains duplicates.
 401 
 402     Parameters
 403     ----------
 404     names : array-like or None
 405         An array containing a list of the names used for the output DataFrame.
 406 
 407     Raises
 408     ------
 409     ValueError
 410         If names are not unique.
 411     """
 412     if names is not None:
 413         if len(names) != len(set(names)):
 414             raise ValueError("Duplicate names are not allowed.")
 415 
 416 
 417 def _read(filepath_or_buffer: FilePathOrBuffer, kwds):
 418     """Generic reader of line files."""
 419     encoding = kwds.get("encoding", None)
 420     if encoding is not None:
 421         encoding = re.sub("_", "-", encoding).lower()
 422         kwds["encoding"] = encoding
 423 
 424     compression = kwds.get("compression", "infer")
 425     compression = infer_compression(filepath_or_buffer, compression)
 426 
 427     # TODO: get_filepath_or_buffer could return
 428     # Union[FilePathOrBuffer, s3fs.S3File, gcsfs.GCSFile]
 429     # though mypy handling of conditional imports is difficult.
 430     # See https://github.com/python/mypy/issues/1297
 431     fp_or_buf, _, compression, should_close = get_filepath_or_buffer(
 432         filepath_or_buffer, encoding, compression
 433     )
 434     kwds["compression"] = compression
 435 
 436     if kwds.get("date_parser", None) is not None:
 437         if isinstance(kwds["parse_dates"], bool):
 438             kwds["parse_dates"] = True
 439 
 440     # Extract some of the arguments (pass chunksize on).
 441     iterator = kwds.get("iterator", False)
 442     chunksize = _validate_integer("chunksize", kwds.get("chunksize", None), 1)
 443     nrows = kwds.get("nrows", None)
 444 
 445     # Check for duplicates in names.
 446     _validate_names(kwds.get("names", None))
 447 
 448     # Create the parser.
 449     parser = TextFileReader(fp_or_buf, **kwds)
 450 
 451     if chunksize or iterator:
 452         return parser
 453 
 454     try:
 455         data = parser.read(nrows)
 456     finally:
 457         parser.close()
 458 
 459     if should_close:
 460         try:
 461             fp_or_buf.close()
 462         except ValueError:
 463             pass
 464 
 465     return data
 466

 468 _parser_defaults = {
 469     "delimiter": None,
 470     "escapechar": None,
 471     "quotechar": '"',
 472     "quoting": csv.QUOTE_MINIMAL,
 473     "doublequote": True,
 474     "skipinitialspace": False,
 475     "lineterminator": None,
 476     "header": "infer",
 477     "index_col": None,
 478     "names": None,
 479     "prefix": None,
 480     "skiprows": None,
 481     "skipfooter": 0,
 482     "nrows": None,
 483     "na_values": None,
 484     "keep_default_na": True,
 485     "true_values": None,
 486     "false_values": None,
 487     "converters": None,
 488     "dtype": None,
 489     "cache_dates": True,
 490     "thousands": None,
 491     "comment": None,
 492     "decimal": ".",
 493     # 'engine': 'c',
 494     "parse_dates": False,
 495     "keep_date_col": False,
 496     "dayfirst": False,
 497     "date_parser": None,
 498     "usecols": None,
 499     # 'iterator': False,
 500     "chunksize": None,
 501     "verbose": False,
 502     "encoding": None,
 503     "squeeze": False,
 504     "compression": None,
 505     "mangle_dupe_cols": True,
 506     "infer_datetime_format": False,
 507     "skip_blank_lines": True,
 508 }
 509 
 510 
 511 _c_parser_defaults = {
 512     "delim_whitespace": False,
 513     "na_filter": True,
 514     "low_memory": True,
 515     "memory_map": False,
 516     "error_bad_lines": True,
 517     "warn_bad_lines": True,
 518     "float_precision": None,
 519 }
 520 
 521 _fwf_defaults = {"colspecs": "infer", "infer_nrows": 100, "widths": None}
 522 
 523 _c_unsupported = {"skipfooter"}
 524 _python_unsupported = {"low_memory", "float_precision"}
 525 
 526 _deprecated_defaults: Dict[str, Any] = {}
 527 _deprecated_args: Set[str] = set()
 528 
 529 
 530 def _make_parser_function(name, default_sep=","):
 531     def parser_f(
 532         filepath_or_buffer: FilePathOrBuffer,
 533         sep=default_sep,
 534         delimiter=None,
 535         # Column and Index Locations and Names
 536         header="infer",
 537         names=None,
 538         index_col=None,
 539         usecols=None,
 540         squeeze=False,
 541         prefix=None,
 542         mangle_dupe_cols=True,
 543         # General Parsing Configuration
 544         dtype=None,
 545         engine=None,
 546         converters=None,
 547         true_values=None,
 548         false_values=None,
 549         skipinitialspace=False,
 550         skiprows=None,
 551         skipfooter=0,
 552         nrows=None,
 553         # NA and Missing Data Handling
 554         na_values=None,
 555         keep_default_na=True,
 556         na_filter=True,
 557         verbose=False,
 558         skip_blank_lines=True,
 559         # Datetime Handling
 560         parse_dates=False,
 561         infer_datetime_format=False,
 562         keep_date_col=False,
 563         date_parser=None,
 564         dayfirst=False,
 565         cache_dates=True,
 566         # Iteration
 567         iterator=False,
 568         chunksize=None,
 569         # Quoting, Compression, and File Format
 570         compression="infer",
 571         thousands=None,
 572         decimal: str = ".",
 573         lineterminator=None,
 574         quotechar='"',
 575         quoting=csv.QUOTE_MINIMAL,
 576         doublequote=True,
 577         escapechar=None,
 578         comment=None,
 579         encoding=None,
 580         dialect=None,
 581         # Error Handling
 582         error_bad_lines=True,
 583         warn_bad_lines=True,
 584         # Internal
 585         delim_whitespace=False,
 586         low_memory=_c_parser_defaults["low_memory"],
 587         memory_map=False,
 588         float_precision=None,
 589     ):
 590 
 591         # gh-23761
 592         #
 593         # When a dialect is passed, it overrides any of the overlapping
 594         # parameters passed in directly. We don't want to warn if the
 595         # default parameters were passed in (since it probably means
 596         # that the user didn't pass them in explicitly in the first place).
 597         #
 598         # "delimiter" is the annoying corner case because we alias it to
 599         # "sep" before doing comparison to the dialect values later on.
 600         # Thus, we need a flag to indicate that we need to "override"
 601         # the comparison to dialect values by checking if default values
 602         # for BOTH "delimiter" and "sep" were provided.
 603         if dialect is not None:
 604             sep_override = delimiter is None and sep == default_sep
 605             kwds = dict(sep_override=sep_override)
 606         else:
 607             kwds = dict()
 608 
 609         # Alias sep -> delimiter.
 610         if delimiter is None:
 611             delimiter = sep
 612 
 613         if delim_whitespace and delimiter != default_sep:
 614             raise ValueError(
 615                 "Specified a delimiter with both sep and "
 616                 "delim_whitespace=True; you can only specify one."
 617             )
 618 
 619         if engine is not None:
 620             engine_specified = True
 621         else:
 622             engine = "c"
 623             engine_specified = False
 624 
 625         kwds.update(
 626             delimiter=delimiter,
 627             engine=engine,
 628             dialect=dialect,
 629             compression=compression,
 630             engine_specified=engine_specified,
 631             doublequote=doublequote,
 632             escapechar=escapechar,
 633             quotechar=quotechar,
 634             quoting=quoting,
 635             skipinitialspace=skipinitialspace,
 636             lineterminator=lineterminator,
 637             header=header,
 638             index_col=index_col,
 639             names=names,
 640             prefix=prefix,
 641             skiprows=skiprows,
 642             skipfooter=skipfooter,
 643             na_values=na_values,
 644             true_values=true_values,
 645             false_values=false_values,
 646             keep_default_na=keep_default_na,
 647             thousands=thousands,
 648             comment=comment,
 649             decimal=decimal,
 650             parse_dates=parse_dates,
 651             keep_date_col=keep_date_col,
 652             dayfirst=dayfirst,
 653             date_parser=date_parser,
 654             cache_dates=cache_dates,
 655             nrows=nrows,
 656             iterator=iterator,
 657             chunksize=chunksize,
 658             converters=converters,
 659             dtype=dtype,
 660             usecols=usecols,
 661             verbose=verbose,
 662             encoding=encoding,
 663             squeeze=squeeze,
 664             memory_map=memory_map,
 665             float_precision=float_precision,
 666             na_filter=na_filter,
 667             delim_whitespace=delim_whitespace,
 668             warn_bad_lines=warn_bad_lines,
 669             error_bad_lines=error_bad_lines,
 670             low_memory=low_memory,
 671             mangle_dupe_cols=mangle_dupe_cols,
 672             infer_datetime_format=infer_datetime_format,
 673             skip_blank_lines=skip_blank_lines,
 674         )
 675 
 676         return _read(filepath_or_buffer, kwds)
 677 
 678     parser_f.__name__ = name
 679 
 680     return parser_f

 701 
 702 def read_fwf(
 703     filepath_or_buffer: FilePathOrBuffer,
 704     colspecs="infer",
 705     widths=None,
 706     infer_nrows=100,
 707     **kwds,
 708 ):
 709     r"""
 710     Read a table of fixed-width formatted lines into DataFrame.
 711 
 712     Also supports optionally iterating or breaking of the file
 713     into chunks.
 714 
 715     Additional help can be found in the `online docs for IO Tools
 716     <https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/user_guide/io.html>`_.
 717 
 718     Parameters
 719     ----------
 720     filepath_or_buffer : str, path object or file-like object
 721         Any valid string path is acceptable. The string could be a URL. Valid
 722         URL schemes include http, ftp, s3, and file. For file URLs, a host is
 723         expected. A local file could be:
 724         ``file://localhost/path/to/table.csv``.
 725 
 726         If you want to pass in a path object, pandas accepts any
 727         ``os.PathLike``.
 728 
 729         By file-like object, we refer to objects with a ``read()`` method,
 730         such as a file handler (e.g. via builtin ``open`` function)
 731         or ``StringIO``.
 732     colspecs : list of tuple (int, int) or 'infer'. optional
 733         A list of tuples giving the extents of the fixed-width
 734         fields of each line as half-open intervals (i.e.,  [from, to[ ).
 735         String value 'infer' can be used to instruct the parser to try
 736         detecting the column specifications from the first 100 rows of
 737         the data which are not being skipped via skiprows (default='infer').
 738     widths : list of int, optional
 739         A list of field widths which can be used instead of 'colspecs' if
 740         the intervals are contiguous.
 741     infer_nrows : int, default 100
 742         The number of rows to consider when letting the parser determine the
 743         `colspecs`.
 744 
 745         .. versionadded:: 0.24.0
 746     **kwds : optional
 747         Optional keyword arguments can be passed to ``TextFileReader``.
 748 
 749     Returns
 750     -------
 751     DataFrame or TextParser
 752         A comma-separated values (csv) file is returned as two-dimensional
 753         data structure with labeled axes.
 754 
 755     See Also
 756     --------
 757     DataFrame.to_csv : Write DataFrame to a comma-separated values (csv) file.
 758     read_csv : Read a comma-separated values (csv) file into DataFrame.
 759 
 760     Examples
 761     --------
 762     >>> pd.read_fwf('data.csv')  # doctest: +SKIP
 763     """
 764     # Check input arguments.
 765     if colspecs is None and widths is None:
 766         raise ValueError("Must specify either colspecs or widths")
 767     elif colspecs not in (None, "infer") and widths is not None:
 768         raise ValueError("You must specify only one of 'widths' and 'colspecs'")
 769 
 770     # Compute 'colspecs' from 'widths', if specified.
 771     if widths is not None:
 772         colspecs, col = [], 0
 773         for w in widths:
 774             colspecs.append((col, col + w))
 775             col += w
 776 
 777     kwds["colspecs"] = colspecs
 778     kwds["infer_nrows"] = infer_nrows
 779     kwds["engine"] = "python-fwf"
 780     return _read(filepath_or_buffer, kwds)
 781 
 782 
 783 class TextFileReader(abc.Iterator):
 784     """
 785 
 786     Passed dialect overrides any of the related parser options
 787 
 788     """
 789 
 790     def __init__(self, f, engine=None, **kwds):
 791 
 792         self.f = f
 793 
 794         if engine is not None:
 795             engine_specified = True
 796         else:
 797             engine = "python"
 798             engine_specified = False
 799 
 800         self._engine_specified = kwds.get("engine_specified", engine_specified)
 801 
 802         if kwds.get("dialect") is not None:
 803             dialect = kwds["dialect"]
 804             if dialect in csv.list_dialects():
 805                 dialect = csv.get_dialect(dialect)
 806 
 807             # Any valid dialect should have these attributes.
 808             # If any are missing, we will raise automatically.
 809             for param in (
 810                 "delimiter",
 811                 "doublequote",
 812                 "escapechar",
 813                 "skipinitialspace",
 814                 "quotechar",
 815                 "quoting",
 816             ):
 817                 try:
 818                     dialect_val = getattr(dialect, param)
 819                 except AttributeError as err:
 820                     raise ValueError(
 821                         f"Invalid dialect {kwds['dialect']} provided"
 822                     ) from err
 823                 parser_default = _parser_defaults[param]
 824                 provided = kwds.get(param, parser_default)
 825 
 826                 # Messages for conflicting values between the dialect
 827                 # instance and the actual parameters provided.
 828                 conflict_msgs = []
 829 
 830                 # Don't warn if the default parameter was passed in,
 831                 # even if it conflicts with the dialect (gh-23761).
 832                 if provided != parser_default and provided != dialect_val:
 833                     msg = (
 834                         f"Conflicting values for '{param}': '{provided}' was "
 835                         f"provided, but the dialect specifies '{dialect_val}'. "
 836                         "Using the dialect-specified value."
 837                     )
 838 
 839                     # Annoying corner case for not warning about
 840                     # conflicts between dialect and delimiter parameter.
 841                     # Refer to the outer "_read_" function for more info.
 842                     if not (param == "delimiter" and kwds.pop("sep_override", False)):
 843                         conflict_msgs.append(msg)
 844 
 845                 if conflict_msgs:
 846                     warnings.warn(
 847                         "\n\n".join(conflict_msgs), ParserWarning, stacklevel=2
 848                     )
 849                 kwds[param] = dialect_val
 850 
 851         if kwds.get("skipfooter"):
 852             if kwds.get("iterator") or kwds.get("chunksize"):
 853                 raise ValueError("'skipfooter' not supported for 'iteration'")
 854             if kwds.get("nrows"):
 855                 raise ValueError("'skipfooter' not supported with 'nrows'")
 856 
 857         if kwds.get("header", "infer") == "infer":
 858             kwds["header"] = 0 if kwds.get("names") is None else None
 859 
 860         self.orig_options = kwds
 861 
 862         # miscellanea
 863         self.engine = engine
 864         self._engine = None
 865         self._currow = 0
 866 
 867         options = self._get_options_with_defaults(engine)
 868 
 869         self.chunksize = options.pop("chunksize", None)
 870         self.nrows = options.pop("nrows", None)
 871         self.squeeze = options.pop("squeeze", False)
 872 
 873         # might mutate self.engine
 874         self.engine = self._check_file_or_buffer(f, engine)
 875         self.options, self.engine = self._clean_options(options, engine)
 876 
 877         if "has_index_names" in kwds:
 878             self.options["has_index_names"] = kwds["has_index_names"]
 879 
 880         self._make_engine(self.engine)
 881 
 882     def close(self):
 883         self._engine.close()
 884 
 885     def _get_options_with_defaults(self, engine):
 886         kwds = self.orig_options
 887 
 888         options = {}
 889 
 890         for argname, default in _parser_defaults.items():
 891             value = kwds.get(argname, default)
 892 
 893             # see gh-12935
 894             if argname == "mangle_dupe_cols" and not value:
 895                 raise ValueError("Setting mangle_dupe_cols=False is not supported yet")
 896             else:
 897                 options[argname] = value
 898 
 899         for argname, default in _c_parser_defaults.items():
 900             if argname in kwds:
 901                 value = kwds[argname]
 902 
 903                 if engine != "c" and value != default:
 904                     if "python" in engine and argname not in _python_unsupported:
 905                         pass
 906                     elif value == _deprecated_defaults.get(argname, default):
 907                         pass
 908                     else:
 909                         raise ValueError(
 910                             f"The {repr(argname)} option is not supported with the "
 911                             f"{repr(engine)} engine"
 912                         )
 913             else:
 914                 value = _deprecated_defaults.get(argname, default)
 915             options[argname] = value
 916 
 917         if engine == "python-fwf":
 918             for argname, default in _fwf_defaults.items():
 919                 options[argname] = kwds.get(argname, default)
 920 
 921         return options
 922 
 923     def _check_file_or_buffer(self, f, engine):
 924         # see gh-16530
 925         if is_file_like(f):
 926             next_attr = "__next__"
 927 
 928             # The C engine doesn't need the file-like to have the "next" or
 929             # "__next__" attribute. However, the Python engine explicitly calls
 930             # "next(...)" when iterating through such an object, meaning it
 931             # needs to have that attribute ("next" for Python 2.x, "__next__"
 932             # for Python 3.x)
 933             if engine != "c" and not hasattr(f, next_attr):
 934                 msg = "The 'python' engine cannot iterate through this file buffer."
 935                 raise ValueError(msg)
 936 
 937         return engine
 938 
 939     def _clean_options(self, options, engine):
 940         result = options.copy()
 941 
 942         engine_specified = self._engine_specified
 943         fallback_reason = None
 944 
 945         sep = options["delimiter"]
 946         delim_whitespace = options["delim_whitespace"]
 947 
 948         # C engine not supported yet
 949         if engine == "c":
 950             if options["skipfooter"] > 0:
 951                 fallback_reason = "the 'c' engine does not support skipfooter"
 952                 engine = "python"
 953 
 954         encoding = sys.getfilesystemencoding() or "utf-8"
 955         if sep is None and not delim_whitespace:
 956             if engine == "c":
 957                 fallback_reason = (
 958                     "the 'c' engine does not support "
 959                     "sep=None with delim_whitespace=False"
 960                 )
 961                 engine = "python"
 962         elif sep is not None and len(sep) > 1:
 963             if engine == "c" and sep == r"\s+":
 964                 result["delim_whitespace"] = True
 965                 del result["delimiter"]
 966             elif engine not in ("python", "python-fwf"):
 967                 # wait until regex engine integrated
 968                 fallback_reason = (
 969                     "the 'c' engine does not support "
 970                     "regex separators (separators > 1 char and "
 971                     r"different from '\s+' are interpreted as regex)"
 972                 )
 973                 engine = "python"
 974         elif delim_whitespace:
 975             if "python" in engine:
 976                 result["delimiter"] = r"\s+"
 977         elif sep is not None:
 978             encodeable = True
 979             try:
 980                 if len(sep.encode(encoding)) > 1:
 981                     encodeable = False
 982             except UnicodeDecodeError:
 983                 encodeable = False
 984             if not encodeable and engine not in ("python", "python-fwf"):
 985                 fallback_reason = (
 986                     f"the separator encoded in {encoding} "
 987                     "is > 1 char long, and the 'c' engine "
 988                     "does not support such separators"
 989                 )
 990                 engine = "python"
 991 
 992         quotechar = options["quotechar"]
 993         if quotechar is not None and isinstance(quotechar, (str, bytes)):
 994             if (
 995                 len(quotechar) == 1
 996                 and ord(quotechar) > 127
 997                 and engine not in ("python", "python-fwf")
 998             ):
 999                 fallback_reason = (
1000                     "ord(quotechar) > 127, meaning the "
1001                     "quotechar is larger than one byte, "
1002                     "and the 'c' engine does not support such quotechars"
1003                 )
1004                 engine = "python"
1005 
1006         if fallback_reason and engine_specified:
1007             raise ValueError(fallback_reason)
1008 
1009         if engine == "c":
1010             for arg in _c_unsupported:
1011                 del result[arg]
1012 
1013         if "python" in engine:
1014             for arg in _python_unsupported:
1015                 if fallback_reason and result[arg] != _c_parser_defaults[arg]:
1016                     raise ValueError(
1017                         "Falling back to the 'python' engine because "
1018                         f"{fallback_reason}, but this causes {repr(arg)} to be "
1019                         "ignored as it is not supported by the 'python' engine."
1020                     )
1021                 del result[arg]
1022 
1023         if fallback_reason:
1024             warnings.warn(
1025                 (
1026                     "Falling back to the 'python' engine because "
1027                     f"{fallback_reason}; you can avoid this warning by specifying "
1028                     "engine='python'."
1029                 ),
1030                 ParserWarning,
1031                 stacklevel=5,
1032             )
1033 
1034         index_col = options["index_col"]
1035         names = options["names"]
1036         converters = options["converters"]
1037         na_values = options["na_values"]
1038         skiprows = options["skiprows"]
1039 
1040         validate_header_arg(options["header"])
1041 
1042         depr_warning = ""
1043 
1044         for arg in _deprecated_args:
1045             parser_default = _c_parser_defaults[arg]
1046             depr_default = _deprecated_defaults[arg]
1047 
1048             msg = (
1049                 f"The {repr(arg)} argument has been deprecated and will be "
1050                 "removed in a future version."
1051             )
1052 
1053             if result.get(arg, depr_default) != depr_default:
1054                 depr_warning += msg + "\n\n"
1055             else:
1056                 result[arg] = parser_default
1057 
1058         if depr_warning != "":
1059             warnings.warn(depr_warning, FutureWarning, stacklevel=2)
1060 
1061         if index_col is True:
1062             raise ValueError("The value of index_col couldn't be 'True'")
1063         if _is_index_col(index_col):
1064             if not isinstance(index_col, (list, tuple, np.ndarray)):
1065                 index_col = [index_col]
1066         result["index_col"] = index_col
1067 
1068         names = list(names) if names is not None else names
1069 
1070         # type conversion-related
1071         if converters is not None:
1072             if not isinstance(converters, dict):
1073                 raise TypeError(
1074                     "Type converters must be a dict or subclass, "
1075                     f"input was a {type(converters).__name__}"
1076                 )
1077         else:
1078             converters = {}
1079 
1080         # Converting values to NA
1081         keep_default_na = options["keep_default_na"]
1082         na_values, na_fvalues = _clean_na_values(na_values, keep_default_na)
1083 
1084         # handle skiprows; this is internally handled by the
1085         # c-engine, so only need for python parsers
1086         if engine != "c":
1087             if is_integer(skiprows):
1088                 skiprows = list(range(skiprows))
1089             if skiprows is None:
1090                 skiprows = set()
1091             elif not callable(skiprows):
1092                 skiprows = set(skiprows)
1093 
1094         # put stuff back
1095         result["names"] = names
1096         result["converters"] = converters
1097         result["na_values"] = na_values
1098         result["na_fvalues"] = na_fvalues
1099         result["skiprows"] = skiprows
1100 
1101         return result, engine
1102 
1103     def __next__(self):
1104         try:
1105             return self.get_chunk()
1106         except StopIteration:
1107             self.close()
1108             raise
1109 
1110     def _make_engine(self, engine="c"):
1111         if engine == "c":
1112             self._engine = CParserWrapper(self.f, **self.options)
1113         else:
1114             if engine == "python":
1115                 klass = PythonParser
1116             elif engine == "python-fwf":
1117                 klass = FixedWidthFieldParser
1118             else:
1119                 raise ValueError(
1120                     f"Unknown engine: {engine} (valid options "
1121                     'are "c", "python", or "python-fwf")'
1122                 )
1123             self._engine = klass(self.f, **self.options)
1124 
1125     def _failover_to_python(self):
1126         raise AbstractMethodError(self)
1127 
1128     def read(self, nrows=None):
1129         nrows = _validate_integer("nrows", nrows)
1130         ret = self._engine.read(nrows)
1131 
1132         # May alter columns / col_dict
1133         index, columns, col_dict = self._create_index(ret)
1134 
1135         if index is None:
1136             if col_dict:
1137                 # Any column is actually fine:
1138                 new_rows = len(next(iter(col_dict.values())))
1139                 index = RangeIndex(self._currow, self._currow + new_rows)
1140             else:
1141                 new_rows = 0
1142         else:
1143             new_rows = len(index)
1144 
1145         df = DataFrame(col_dict, columns=columns, index=index)
1146 
1147         self._currow += new_rows
1148 
1149         if self.squeeze and len(df.columns) == 1:
1150             return df[df.columns[0]].copy()
1151         return df
1152 
1153     def _create_index(self, ret):
1154         index, columns, col_dict = ret
1155         return index, columns, col_dict
1156 
1157     def get_chunk(self, size=None):
1158         if size is None:
1159             size = self.chunksize
1160         if self.nrows is not None:
1161             if self._currow >= self.nrows:
1162                 raise StopIteration
1163             size = min(size, self.nrows - self._currow)
1164         return self.read(nrows=size)
1165 
1166 
1167 def _is_index_col(col):
1168     return col is not None and col is not False
1169 
1170 
1171 def _is_potential_multi_index(
1172     columns, index_col: Optional[Union[bool, Sequence[int]]] = None
1173 ):
1174     """
1175     Check whether or not the `columns` parameter
1176     could be converted into a MultiIndex.
1177 
1178     Parameters
1179     ----------
1180     columns : array-like
1181         Object which may or may not be convertible into a MultiIndex
1182     index_col : None, bool or list, optional
1183         Column or columns to use as the (possibly hierarchical) index
1184 
1185     Returns
1186     -------
1187     boolean : Whether or not columns could become a MultiIndex
1188     """
1189     if index_col is None or isinstance(index_col, bool):
1190         index_col = []
1191 
1192     return (
1193         len(columns)
1194         and not isinstance(columns, MultiIndex)
1195         and all(isinstance(c, tuple) for c in columns if c not in list(index_col))
1196     )

1199 def _evaluate_usecols(usecols, names):
1200     """
1201     Check whether or not the 'usecols' parameter
1202     is a callable.  If so, enumerates the 'names'
1203     parameter and returns a set of indices for
1204     each entry in 'names' that evaluates to True.
1205     If not a callable, returns 'usecols'.
1206     """
1207     if callable(usecols):
1208         return {i for i, name in enumerate(names) if usecols(name)}
1209     return usecols

1212 def _validate_usecols_names(usecols, names):
1213     """
1214     Validates that all usecols are present in a given
1215     list of names. If not, raise a ValueError that
1216     shows what usecols are missing.
1217 
1218     Parameters
1219     ----------
1220     usecols : iterable of usecols
1221         The columns to validate are present in names.
1222     names : iterable of names
1223         The column names to check against.
1224 
1225     Returns
1226     -------
1227     usecols : iterable of usecols
1228         The `usecols` parameter if the validation succeeds.
1229 
1230     Raises
1231     ------
1232     ValueError : Columns were missing. Error message will list them.
1233     """
1234     missing = [c for c in usecols if c not in names]
1235     if len(missing) > 0:
1236         raise ValueError(
1237             f"Usecols do not match columns, columns expected but not found: {missing}"
1238         )
1239 
1240     return usecols

1243 def _validate_skipfooter_arg(skipfooter):
1244     """
1245     Validate the 'skipfooter' parameter.
1246 
1247     Checks whether 'skipfooter' is a non-negative integer.
1248     Raises a ValueError if that is not the case.
1249 
1250     Parameters
1251     ----------
1252     skipfooter : non-negative integer
1253         The number of rows to skip at the end of the file.
1254 
1255     Returns
1256     -------
1257     validated_skipfooter : non-negative integer
1258         The original input if the validation succeeds.
1259 
1260     Raises
1261     ------
1262     ValueError : 'skipfooter' was not a non-negative integer.
1263     """
1264     if not is_integer(skipfooter):
1265         raise ValueError("skipfooter must be an integer")
1266 
1267     if skipfooter < 0:
1268         raise ValueError("skipfooter cannot be negative")
1269 
1270     return skipfooter

1273 def _validate_usecols_arg(usecols):
1274     """
1275     Validate the 'usecols' parameter.
1276 
1277     Checks whether or not the 'usecols' parameter contains all integers
1278     (column selection by index), strings (column by name) or is a callable.
1279     Raises a ValueError if that is not the case.
1280 
1281     Parameters
1282     ----------
1283     usecols : list-like, callable, or None
1284         List of columns to use when parsing or a callable that can be used
1285         to filter a list of table columns.
1286 
1287     Returns
1288     -------
1289     usecols_tuple : tuple
1290         A tuple of (verified_usecols, usecols_dtype).
1291 
1292         'verified_usecols' is either a set if an array-like is passed in or
1293         'usecols' if a callable or None is passed in.
1294 
1295         'usecols_dtype` is the inferred dtype of 'usecols' if an array-like
1296         is passed in or None if a callable or None is passed in.
1297     """
1298     msg = (
1299         "'usecols' must either be list-like of all strings, all unicode, "
1300         "all integers or a callable."
1301     )
1302     if usecols is not None:
1303         if callable(usecols):
1304             return usecols, None
1305 
1306         if not is_list_like(usecols):
1307             # see gh-20529
1308             #
1309             # Ensure it is iterable container but not string.
1310             raise ValueError(msg)
1311 
1312         usecols_dtype = lib.infer_dtype(usecols, skipna=False)
1313 
1314         if usecols_dtype not in ("empty", "integer", "string"):
1315             raise ValueError(msg)
1316 
1317         usecols = set(usecols)
1318 
1319         return usecols, usecols_dtype
1320     return usecols, None

1323 def _validate_parse_dates_arg(parse_dates):
1324     """
1325     Check whether or not the 'parse_dates' parameter
1326     is a non-boolean scalar. Raises a ValueError if
1327     that is the case.
1328     """
1329     msg = (
1330         "Only booleans, lists, and dictionaries are accepted "
1331         "for the 'parse_dates' parameter"
1332     )
1333 
1334     if parse_dates is not None:
1335         if is_scalar(parse_dates):
1336             if not lib.is_bool(parse_dates):
1337                 raise TypeError(msg)
1338 
1339         elif not isinstance(parse_dates, (list, dict)):
1340             raise TypeError(msg)
1341 
1342     return parse_dates

1345 class ParserBase:
1346     def __init__(self, kwds):
1347         self.names = kwds.get("names")
1348         self.orig_names = None
1349         self.prefix = kwds.pop("prefix", None)
1350 
1351         self.index_col = kwds.get("index_col", None)
1352         self.unnamed_cols = set()
1353         self.index_names = None
1354         self.col_names = None
1355 
1356         self.parse_dates = _validate_parse_dates_arg(kwds.pop("parse_dates", False))
1357         self.date_parser = kwds.pop("date_parser", None)
1358         self.dayfirst = kwds.pop("dayfirst", False)
1359         self.keep_date_col = kwds.pop("keep_date_col", False)
1360 
1361         self.na_values = kwds.get("na_values")
1362         self.na_fvalues = kwds.get("na_fvalues")
1363         self.na_filter = kwds.get("na_filter", False)
1364         self.keep_default_na = kwds.get("keep_default_na", True)
1365 
1366         self.true_values = kwds.get("true_values")
1367         self.false_values = kwds.get("false_values")
1368         self.mangle_dupe_cols = kwds.get("mangle_dupe_cols", True)
1369         self.infer_datetime_format = kwds.pop("infer_datetime_format", False)
1370         self.cache_dates = kwds.pop("cache_dates", True)
1371 
1372         self._date_conv = _make_date_converter(
1373             date_parser=self.date_parser,
1374             dayfirst=self.dayfirst,
1375             infer_datetime_format=self.infer_datetime_format,
1376             cache_dates=self.cache_dates,
1377         )
1378 
1379         # validate header options for mi
1380         self.header = kwds.get("header")
1381         if isinstance(self.header, (list, tuple, np.ndarray)):
1382             if not all(map(is_integer, self.header)):
1383                 raise ValueError("header must be integer or list of integers")
1384             if any(i < 0 for i in self.header):
1385                 raise ValueError(
1386                     "cannot specify multi-index header with negative integers"
1387                 )
1388             if kwds.get("usecols"):
1389                 raise ValueError(
1390                     "cannot specify usecols when specifying a multi-index header"
1391                 )
1392             if kwds.get("names"):
1393                 raise ValueError(
1394                     "cannot specify names when specifying a multi-index header"
1395                 )
1396 
1397             # validate index_col that only contains integers
1398             if self.index_col is not None:
1399                 is_sequence = isinstance(self.index_col, (list, tuple, np.ndarray))
1400                 if not (
1401                     is_sequence
1402                     and all(map(is_integer, self.index_col))
1403                     or is_integer(self.index_col)
1404                 ):
1405                     raise ValueError(
1406                         "index_col must only contain row numbers "
1407                         "when specifying a multi-index header"
1408                     )
1409         elif self.header is not None:
1410             # GH 27394
1411             if self.prefix is not None:
1412                 raise ValueError(
1413                     "Argument prefix must be None if argument header is not None"
1414                 )
1415             # GH 16338
1416             elif not is_integer(self.header):
1417                 raise ValueError("header must be integer or list of integers")
1418             # GH 27779
1419             elif self.header < 0:
1420                 raise ValueError(
1421                     "Passing negative integer to header is invalid. "
1422                     "For no header, use header=None instead"
1423                 )
1424 
1425         self._name_processed = False
1426 
1427         self._first_chunk = True
1428 
1429         # GH 13932
1430         # keep references to file handles opened by the parser itself
1431         self.handles = []

1433     def _validate_parse_dates_presence(self, columns: List[str]) -> None:
1434         """
1435         Check if parse_dates are in columns.
1436 
1437         If user has provided names for parse_dates, check if those columns
1438         are available.
1439 
1440         Parameters
1441         ----------
1442         columns : list
1443             List of names of the dataframe.
1444 
1445         Raises
1446         ------
1447         ValueError
1448             If column to parse_date is not in dataframe.
1449 
1450         """
1451         cols_needed: Iterable
1452         if is_dict_like(self.parse_dates):
1453             cols_needed = itertools.chain(*self.parse_dates.values())
1454         elif is_list_like(self.parse_dates):
1455             # a column in parse_dates could be represented
1456             # ColReference = Union[int, str]
1457             # DateGroups = List[ColReference]
1458             # ParseDates = Union[DateGroups, List[DateGroups],
1459             #     Dict[ColReference, DateGroups]]
1460             cols_needed = itertools.chain.from_iterable(
1461                 col if is_list_like(col) else [col] for col in self.parse_dates
1462             )
1463         else:
1464             cols_needed = []
1465 
1466         # get only columns that are references using names (str), not by index
1467         missing_cols = ", ".join(
1468             sorted(
1469                 {
1470                     col
1471                     for col in cols_needed
1472                     if isinstance(col, str) and col not in columns
1473                 }
1474             )
1475         )
1476         if missing_cols:
1477             raise ValueError(
1478                 f"Missing column provided to 'parse_dates': '{missing_cols}'"
1479             )
1480 
1481     def close(self):
1482         for f in self.handles:
1483             f.close()

1485     @property
1486     def _has_complex_date_col(self):
1487         return isinstance(self.parse_dates, dict) or (
1488             isinstance(self.parse_dates, list)
1489             and len(self.parse_dates) > 0
1490             and isinstance(self.parse_dates[0], list)
1491         )

1493     def _should_parse_dates(self, i):
1494         if isinstance(self.parse_dates, bool):
1495             return self.parse_dates
1496         else:
1497             if self.index_names is not None:
1498                 name = self.index_names[i]
1499             else:
1500                 name = None
1501             j = self.index_col[i]
1502 
1503             if is_scalar(self.parse_dates):
1504                 return (j == self.parse_dates) or (
1505                     name is not None and name == self.parse_dates
1506                 )
1507             else:
1508                 return (j in self.parse_dates) or (
1509                     name is not None and name in self.parse_dates
1510                 )

1512     def _extract_multi_indexer_columns(
1513         self, header, index_names, col_names, passed_names=False
1514     ):
1515         """
1516         extract and return the names, index_names, col_names
1517         header is a list-of-lists returned from the parsers
1518         """
1519         if len(header) < 2:
1520             return header[0], index_names, col_names, passed_names
1521 
1522         # the names are the tuples of the header that are not the index cols
1523         # 0 is the name of the index, assuming index_col is a list of column
1524         # numbers
1525         ic = self.index_col
1526         if ic is None:
1527             ic = []
1528 
1529         if not isinstance(ic, (list, tuple, np.ndarray)):
1530             ic = [ic]
1531         sic = set(ic)
1532 
1533         # clean the index_names
1534         index_names = header.pop(-1)
1535         index_names, names, index_col = _clean_index_names(
1536             index_names, self.index_col, self.unnamed_cols
1537         )
1538 
1539         # extract the columns
1540         field_count = len(header[0])
1541 
1542         def extract(r):
1543             return tuple(r[i] for i in range(field_count) if i not in sic)
1544 
1545         columns = list(zip(*(extract(r) for r in header)))
1546         names = ic + columns
1547 
1548         # If we find unnamed columns all in a single
1549         # level, then our header was too long.
1550         for n in range(len(columns[0])):
1551             if all(ensure_str(col[n]) in self.unnamed_cols for col in columns):
1552                 header = ",".join(str(x) for x in self.header)
1553                 raise ParserError(
1554                     f"Passed header=[{header}] are too many rows "
1555                     "for this multi_index of columns"
1556                 )
1557 
1558         # Clean the column names (if we have an index_col).
1559         if len(ic):
1560             col_names = [
1561                 r[0] if (len(r[0]) and r[0] not in self.unnamed_cols) else None
1562                 for r in header
1563             ]
1564         else:
1565             col_names = [None] * len(header)
1566 
1567         passed_names = True
1568 
1569         return names, index_names, col_names, passed_names
1570 
1571     def _maybe_dedup_names(self, names):
1572         # see gh-7160 and gh-9424: this helps to provide
1573         # immediate alleviation of the duplicate names
1574         # issue and appears to be satisfactory to users,
1575         # but ultimately, not needing to butcher the names
1576         # would be nice!
1577         if self.mangle_dupe_cols:
1578             names = list(names)  # so we can index
1579             counts = defaultdict(int)
1580             is_potential_mi = _is_potential_multi_index(names, self.index_col)
1581 
1582             for i, col in enumerate(names):
1583                 cur_count = counts[col]
1584 
1585                 while cur_count > 0:
1586                     counts[col] = cur_count + 1
1587 
1588                     if is_potential_mi:
1589                         col = col[:-1] + (f"{col[-1]}.{cur_count}",)
1590                     else:
1591                         col = f"{col}.{cur_count}"
1592                     cur_count = counts[col]
1593 
1594                 names[i] = col
1595                 counts[col] = cur_count + 1
1596 
1597         return names
1598 
1599     def _maybe_make_multi_index_columns(self, columns, col_names=None):
1600         # possibly create a column mi here
1601         if _is_potential_multi_index(columns):
1602             columns = MultiIndex.from_tuples(columns, names=col_names)
1603         return columns
1604 
1605     def _make_index(self, data, alldata, columns, indexnamerow=False):
1606         if not _is_index_col(self.index_col) or not self.index_col:
1607             index = None
1608 
1609         elif not self._has_complex_date_col:
1610             index = self._get_simple_index(alldata, columns)
1611             index = self._agg_index(index)
1612         elif self._has_complex_date_col:
1613             if not self._name_processed:
1614                 (self.index_names, _, self.index_col) = _clean_index_names(
1615                     list(columns), self.index_col, self.unnamed_cols
1616                 )
1617                 self._name_processed = True
1618             index = self._get_complex_date_index(data, columns)
1619             index = self._agg_index(index, try_parse_dates=False)
1620 
1621         # add names for the index
1622         if indexnamerow:
1623             coffset = len(indexnamerow) - len(columns)
1624             index = index.set_names(indexnamerow[:coffset])
1625 
1626         # maybe create a mi on the columns
1627         columns = self._maybe_make_multi_index_columns(columns, self.col_names)
1628 
1629         return index, columns
1630 
1631     _implicit_index = False
1632 
1633     def _get_simple_index(self, data, columns):
1634         def ix(col):
1635             if not isinstance(col, str):
1636                 return col
1637             raise ValueError(f"Index {col} invalid")
1638 
1639         to_remove = []
1640         index = []
1641         for idx in self.index_col:
1642             i = ix(idx)
1643             to_remove.append(i)
1644             index.append(data[i])
1645 
1646         # remove index items from content and columns, don't pop in
1647         # loop
1648         for i in sorted(to_remove, reverse=True):
1649             data.pop(i)
1650             if not self._implicit_index:
1651                 columns.pop(i)
1652 
1653         return index
1654 
1655     def _get_complex_date_index(self, data, col_names):
1656         def _get_name(icol):
1657             if isinstance(icol, str):
1658                 return icol
1659 
1660             if col_names is None:
1661                 raise ValueError(f"Must supply column order to use {icol!s} as index")
1662 
1663             for i, c in enumerate(col_names):
1664                 if i == icol:
1665                     return c
1666 
1667         to_remove = []
1668         index = []
1669         for idx in self.index_col:
1670             name = _get_name(idx)
1671             to_remove.append(name)
1672             index.append(data[name])
1673 
1674         # remove index items from content and columns, don't pop in
1675         # loop
1676         for c in sorted(to_remove, reverse=True):
1677             data.pop(c)
1678             col_names.remove(c)
1679 
1680         return index
1681 
1682     def _agg_index(self, index, try_parse_dates=True):
1683         arrays = []
1684 
1685         for i, arr in enumerate(index):
1686 
1687             if try_parse_dates and self._should_parse_dates(i):
1688                 arr = self._date_conv(arr)
1689 
1690             if self.na_filter:
1691                 col_na_values = self.na_values
1692                 col_na_fvalues = self.na_fvalues
1693             else:
1694                 col_na_values = set()
1695                 col_na_fvalues = set()
1696 
1697             if isinstance(self.na_values, dict):
1698                 col_name = self.index_names[i]
1699                 if col_name is not None:
1700                     col_na_values, col_na_fvalues = _get_na_values(
1701                         col_name, self.na_values, self.na_fvalues, self.keep_default_na
1702                     )
1703 
1704             arr, _ = self._infer_types(arr, col_na_values | col_na_fvalues)
1705             arrays.append(arr)
1706 
1707         names = self.index_names
1708         index = ensure_index_from_sequences(arrays, names)
1709 
1710         return index
1711 
1712     def _convert_to_ndarrays(
1713         self, dct, na_values, na_fvalues, verbose=False, converters=None, dtypes=None
1714     ):
1715         result = {}
1716         for c, values in dct.items():
1717             conv_f = None if converters is None else converters.get(c, None)
1718             if isinstance(dtypes, dict):
1719                 cast_type = dtypes.get(c, None)
1720             else:
1721                 # single dtype or None
1722                 cast_type = dtypes
1723 
1724             if self.na_filter:
1725                 col_na_values, col_na_fvalues = _get_na_values(
1726                     c, na_values, na_fvalues, self.keep_default_na
1727                 )
1728             else:
1729                 col_na_values, col_na_fvalues = set(), set()
1730 
1731             if conv_f is not None:
1732                 # conv_f applied to data before inference
1733                 if cast_type is not None:
1734                     warnings.warn(
1735                         (
1736                             "Both a converter and dtype were specified "
1737                             f"for column {c} - only the converter will be used"
1738                         ),
1739                         ParserWarning,
1740                         stacklevel=7,
1741                     )
1742 
1743                 try:
1744                     values = lib.map_infer(values, conv_f)
1745                 except ValueError:
1746                     mask = algorithms.isin(values, list(na_values)).view(np.uint8)
1747                     values = lib.map_infer_mask(values, conv_f, mask)
1748 
1749                 cvals, na_count = self._infer_types(
1750                     values, set(col_na_values) | col_na_fvalues, try_num_bool=False
1751                 )
1752             else:
1753                 is_str_or_ea_dtype = is_string_dtype(
1754                     cast_type
1755                 ) or is_extension_array_dtype(cast_type)
1756                 # skip inference if specified dtype is object
1757                 # or casting to an EA
1758                 try_num_bool = not (cast_type and is_str_or_ea_dtype)
1759 
1760                 # general type inference and conversion
1761                 cvals, na_count = self._infer_types(
1762                     values, set(col_na_values) | col_na_fvalues, try_num_bool
1763                 )
1764 
1765                 # type specified in dtype param or cast_type is an EA
1766                 if cast_type and (
1767                     not is_dtype_equal(cvals, cast_type)
1768                     or is_extension_array_dtype(cast_type)
1769                 ):
1770                     try:
1771                         if (
1772                             is_bool_dtype(cast_type)
1773                             and not is_categorical_dtype(cast_type)
1774                             and na_count > 0
1775                         ):
1776                             raise ValueError(f"Bool column has NA values in column {c}")
1777                     except (AttributeError, TypeError):
1778                         # invalid input to is_bool_dtype
1779                         pass
1780                     cvals = self._cast_types(cvals, cast_type, c)
1781 
1782             result[c] = cvals
1783             if verbose and na_count:
1784                 print(f"Filled {na_count} NA values in column {c!s}")
1785         return result
1786 
1787     def _infer_types(self, values, na_values, try_num_bool=True):
1788         """
1789         Infer types of values, possibly casting
1790 
1791         Parameters
1792         ----------
1793         values : ndarray
1794         na_values : set
1795         try_num_bool : bool, default try
1796            try to cast values to numeric (first preference) or boolean
1797 
1798         Returns
1799         -------
1800         converted : ndarray
1801         na_count : int
1802         """
1803         na_count = 0
1804         if issubclass(values.dtype.type, (np.number, np.bool_)):
1805             mask = algorithms.isin(values, list(na_values))
1806             na_count = mask.sum()
1807             if na_count > 0:
1808                 if is_integer_dtype(values):
1809                     values = values.astype(np.float64)
1810                 np.putmask(values, mask, np.nan)
1811             return values, na_count
1812 
1813         if try_num_bool and is_object_dtype(values.dtype):
1814             # exclude e.g DatetimeIndex here
1815             try:
1816                 result = lib.maybe_convert_numeric(values, na_values, False)
1817             except (ValueError, TypeError):
1818                 # e.g. encountering datetime string gets ValueError
1819                 #  TypeError can be raised in floatify
1820                 result = values
1821                 na_count = parsers.sanitize_objects(result, na_values, False)
1822             else:
1823                 na_count = isna(result).sum()
1824         else:
1825             result = values
1826             if values.dtype == np.object_:
1827                 na_count = parsers.sanitize_objects(values, na_values, False)
1828 
1829         if result.dtype == np.object_ and try_num_bool:
1830             result = libops.maybe_convert_bool(
1831                 np.asarray(values),
1832                 true_values=self.true_values,
1833                 false_values=self.false_values,
1834             )
1835 
1836         return result, na_count
1837 
1838     def _cast_types(self, values, cast_type, column):
1839         """
1840         Cast values to specified type
1841 
1842         Parameters
1843         ----------
1844         values : ndarray
1845         cast_type : string or np.dtype
1846            dtype to cast values to
1847         column : string
1848             column name - used only for error reporting
1849 
1850         Returns
1851         -------
1852         converted : ndarray
1853         """
1854         if is_categorical_dtype(cast_type):
1855             known_cats = (
1856                 isinstance(cast_type, CategoricalDtype)
1857                 and cast_type.categories is not None
1858             )
1859 
1860             if not is_object_dtype(values) and not known_cats:
1861                 # TODO: this is for consistency with
1862                 # c-parser which parses all categories
1863                 # as strings
1864                 values = astype_nansafe(values, str)
1865 
1866             cats = Index(values).unique().dropna()
1867             values = Categorical._from_inferred_categories(
1868                 cats, cats.get_indexer(values), cast_type, true_values=self.true_values
1869             )
1870 
1871         # use the EA's implementation of casting
1872         elif is_extension_array_dtype(cast_type):
1873             # ensure cast_type is an actual dtype and not a string
1874             cast_type = pandas_dtype(cast_type)
1875             array_type = cast_type.construct_array_type()
1876             try:
1877                 return array_type._from_sequence_of_strings(values, dtype=cast_type)
1878             except NotImplementedError as err:
1879                 raise NotImplementedError(
1880                     f"Extension Array: {array_type} must implement "
1881                     "_from_sequence_of_strings in order to be used in parser methods"
1882                 ) from err
1883 
1884         else:
1885             try:
1886                 values = astype_nansafe(values, cast_type, copy=True, skipna=True)
1887             except ValueError as err:
1888                 raise ValueError(
1889                     f"Unable to convert column {column} to type {cast_type}"
1890                 ) from err
1891         return values
1892 
1893     def _do_date_conversions(self, names, data):
1894         # returns data, columns
1895 
1896         if self.parse_dates is not None:
1897             data, names = _process_date_conversion(
1898                 data,
1899                 self._date_conv,
1900                 self.parse_dates,
1901                 self.index_col,
1902                 self.index_names,
1903                 names,
1904                 keep_date_col=self.keep_date_col,
1905             )
1906 
1907         return names, data

2198 def TextParser(*args, **kwds):
2199     """
2200     Converts lists of lists/tuples into DataFrames with proper type inference
2201     and optional (e.g. string to datetime) conversion. Also enables iterating
2202     lazily over chunks of large files
2203 
2204     Parameters
2205     ----------
2206     data : file-like object or list
2207     delimiter : separator character to use
2208     dialect : str or csv.Dialect instance, optional
2209         Ignored if delimiter is longer than 1 character
2210     names : sequence, default
2211     header : int, default 0
2212         Row to use to parse column labels. Defaults to the first row. Prior
2213         rows will be discarded
2214     index_col : int or list, optional
2215         Column or columns to use as the (possibly hierarchical) index
2216     has_index_names: bool, default False
2217         True if the cols defined in index_col have an index name and are
2218         not in the header.
2219     na_values : scalar, str, list-like, or dict, optional
2220         Additional strings to recognize as NA/NaN.
2221     keep_default_na : bool, default True
2222     thousands : str, optional
2223         Thousands separator
2224     comment : str, optional
2225         Comment out remainder of line
2226     parse_dates : bool, default False
2227     keep_date_col : bool, default False
2228     date_parser : function, optional
2229     skiprows : list of integers
2230         Row numbers to skip
2231     skipfooter : int
2232         Number of line at bottom of file to skip
2233     converters : dict, optional
2234         Dict of functions for converting values in certain columns. Keys can
2235         either be integers or column labels, values are functions that take one
2236         input argument, the cell (not column) content, and return the
2237         transformed content.
2238     encoding : str, optional
2239         Encoding to use for UTF when reading/writing (ex. 'utf-8')
2240     squeeze : bool, default False
2241         returns Series if only one column.
2242     infer_datetime_format: bool, default False
2243         If True and `parse_dates` is True for a column, try to infer the
2244         datetime format based on the first datetime string. If the format
2245         can be inferred, there often will be a large parsing speed-up.
2246     float_precision : str, optional
2247         Specifies which converter the C engine should use for floating-point
2248         values. The options are None for the ordinary converter,
2249         'high' for the high-precision converter, and 'round_trip' for the
2250         round-trip converter.
2251     """
2252     kwds["engine"] = "python"
2253     return TextFileReader(*args, **kwds)
2254

2256 def count_empty_vals(vals):
2257     return sum(1 for v in vals if v == "" or v is None)
