2425     def _make_reader(self, f):
2426         sep = self.delimiter
2427 
2428         if sep is None or len(sep) == 1:
2429             if self.lineterminator:
2430                 raise ValueError(
2431                     "Custom line terminators not supported in python parser (yet)"
2432                 )
2433 
2434             class MyDialect(csv.Dialect):
2435                 delimiter = self.delimiter
2436                 quotechar = self.quotechar
2437                 escapechar = self.escapechar
2438                 doublequote = self.doublequote
2439                 skipinitialspace = self.skipinitialspace
2440                 quoting = self.quoting
2441                 lineterminator = "\n"
2442 
2443             dia = MyDialect
2444 
2445             if sep is not None:
2446                 dia.delimiter = sep
2447             else:
2448                 # attempt to sniff the delimiter from the first valid line,
2449                 # i.e. no comment line and not in skiprows
2450                 line = f.readline()
2451                 lines = self._check_comments([[line]])[0]
2452                 while self.skipfunc(self.pos) or not lines:
2453                     self.pos += 1
2454                     line = f.readline()
2455                     lines = self._check_comments([[line]])[0]
2456 
2457                 # since `line` was a string, lines will be a list containing
2458                 # only a single string
2459                 line = lines[0]
2460 
2461                 self.pos += 1
2462                 self.line_pos += 1
2463                 sniffed = csv.Sniffer().sniff(line)
2464                 dia.delimiter = sniffed.delimiter
2465 
2466                 # Note: self.encoding is irrelevant here
2467                 line_rdr = csv.reader(StringIO(line), dialect=dia)
2468                 self.buf.extend(list(line_rdr))
2469 
2470             # Note: self.encoding is irrelevant here
2471             reader = csv.reader(f, dialect=dia, strict=True)
2472 
2473         else:
2474 
2475             def _read():
2476                 line = f.readline()
2477                 pat = re.compile(sep)
2478 
2479                 yield pat.split(line.strip())
2480 
2481                 for line in f:
2482                     yield pat.split(line.strip())
2483 
2484             reader = _read()
2485 
2486         self.data = reader
2487 
2488     def read(self, rows=None):
2489         try:
2490             content = self._get_lines(rows)
2491         except StopIteration:
2492             if self._first_chunk:
2493                 content = []
2494             else:
2495                 raise
2496 
2497         # done with first read, next time raise StopIteration
2498         self._first_chunk = False
2499 
2500         columns = list(self.orig_names)
2501         if not len(content):  # pragma: no cover
2502             # DataFrame with the right metadata, even though it's length 0
2503             names = self._maybe_dedup_names(self.orig_names)
2504             index, columns, col_dict = _get_empty_meta(
2505                 names, self.index_col, self.index_names, self.dtype
2506             )
2507             columns = self._maybe_make_multi_index_columns(columns, self.col_names)
2508             return index, columns, col_dict
2509 
2510         # handle new style for names in index
2511         count_empty_content_vals = count_empty_vals(content[0])
2512         indexnamerow = None
2513         if self.has_index_names and count_empty_content_vals == len(columns):
2514             indexnamerow = content[0]
2515             content = content[1:]
2516 
2517         alldata = self._rows_to_cols(content)
2518         data = self._exclude_implicit_index(alldata)
2519 
2520         columns = self._maybe_dedup_names(self.columns)
2521         columns, data = self._do_date_conversions(columns, data)
2522 
2523         data = self._convert_data(data)
2524         index, columns = self._make_index(data, alldata, columns, indexnamerow)
2525 
2526         return index, columns, data

2528     def _exclude_implicit_index(self, alldata):
2529         names = self._maybe_dedup_names(self.orig_names)
2530 
2531         if self._implicit_index:
2532             excl_indices = self.index_col
2533 
2534             data = {}
2535             offset = 0
2536             for i, col in enumerate(names):
2537                 while i + offset in excl_indices:
2538                     offset += 1
2539                 data[col] = alldata[i + offset]
2540         else:
2541             data = {k: v for k, v in zip(names, alldata)}
2542 
2543         return data

2551     def _convert_data(self, data):
2552         # apply converters
2553         def _clean_mapping(mapping):
2554             """converts col numbers to names"""
2555             clean = {}
2556             for col, v in mapping.items():
2557                 if isinstance(col, int) and col not in self.orig_names:
2558                     col = self.orig_names[col]
2559                 clean[col] = v
2560             return clean
2561 
2562         clean_conv = _clean_mapping(self.converters)
2563         if not isinstance(self.dtype, dict):
2564             # handles single dtype applied to all columns
2565             clean_dtypes = self.dtype
2566         else:
2567             clean_dtypes = _clean_mapping(self.dtype)
2568 
2569         # Apply NA values.
2570         clean_na_values = {}
2571         clean_na_fvalues = {}
2572 
2573         if isinstance(self.na_values, dict):
2574             for col in self.na_values:
2575                 na_value = self.na_values[col]
2576                 na_fvalue = self.na_fvalues[col]
2577 
2578                 if isinstance(col, int) and col not in self.orig_names:
2579                     col = self.orig_names[col]
2580 
2581                 clean_na_values[col] = na_value
2582                 clean_na_fvalues[col] = na_fvalue
2583         else:
2584             clean_na_values = self.na_values
2585             clean_na_fvalues = self.na_fvalues
2586 
2587         return self._convert_to_ndarrays(
2588             data,
2589             clean_na_values,
2590             clean_na_fvalues,
2591             self.verbose,
2592             clean_conv,
2593             clean_dtypes,
2594         )

2596     def _infer_columns(self):
2597         names = self.names
2598         num_original_columns = 0
2599         clear_buffer = True
2600         unnamed_cols = set()
2601 
2602         if self.header is not None:
2603             header = self.header
2604 
2605             if isinstance(header, (list, tuple, np.ndarray)):
2606                 have_mi_columns = len(header) > 1
2607                 # we have a mi columns, so read an extra line
2608                 if have_mi_columns:
2609                     header = list(header) + [header[-1] + 1]
2610             else:
2611                 have_mi_columns = False
2612                 header = [header]
2613 
2614             columns = []
2615             for level, hr in enumerate(header):
2616                 try:
2617                     line = self._buffered_line()
2618 
2619                     while self.line_pos <= hr:
2620                         line = self._next_line()
2621 
2622                 except StopIteration as err:
2623                     if self.line_pos < hr:
2624                         raise ValueError(
2625                             f"Passed header={hr} but only {self.line_pos + 1} lines in "
2626                             "file"
2627                         ) from err
2628 
2629                     # We have an empty file, so check
2630                     # if columns are provided. That will
2631                     # serve as the 'line' for parsing
2632                     if have_mi_columns and hr > 0:
2633                         if clear_buffer:
2634                             self._clear_buffer()
2635                         columns.append([None] * len(columns[-1]))
2636                         return columns, num_original_columns, unnamed_cols
2637 
2638                     if not self.names:
2639                         raise EmptyDataError("No columns to parse from file") from err
2640 
2641                     line = self.names[:]
2642 
2643                 this_columns = []
2644                 this_unnamed_cols = []
2645 
2646                 for i, c in enumerate(line):
2647                     if c == "":
2648                         if have_mi_columns:
2649                             col_name = f"Unnamed: {i}_level_{level}"
2650                         else:
2651                             col_name = f"Unnamed: {i}"
2652 
2653                         this_unnamed_cols.append(i)
2654                         this_columns.append(col_name)
2655                     else:
2656                         this_columns.append(c)
2657 
2658                 if not have_mi_columns and self.mangle_dupe_cols:
2659                     counts = defaultdict(int)
2660 
2661                     for i, col in enumerate(this_columns):
2662                         cur_count = counts[col]
2663 
2664                         while cur_count > 0:
2665                             counts[col] = cur_count + 1
2666                             col = f"{col}.{cur_count}"
2667                             cur_count = counts[col]
2668 
2669                         this_columns[i] = col
2670                         counts[col] = cur_count + 1
2671                 elif have_mi_columns:
2672 
2673                     # if we have grabbed an extra line, but its not in our
2674                     # format so save in the buffer, and create an blank extra
2675                     # line for the rest of the parsing code
2676                     if hr == header[-1]:
2677                         lc = len(this_columns)
2678                         ic = len(self.index_col) if self.index_col is not None else 0
2679                         unnamed_count = len(this_unnamed_cols)
2680 
2681                         if lc != unnamed_count and lc - ic > unnamed_count:
2682                             clear_buffer = False
2683                             this_columns = [None] * lc
2684                             self.buf = [self.buf[-1]]
2685 
2686                 columns.append(this_columns)
2687                 unnamed_cols.update({this_columns[i] for i in this_unnamed_cols})
2688 
2689                 if len(columns) == 1:
2690                     num_original_columns = len(this_columns)
2691 
2692             if clear_buffer:
2693                 self._clear_buffer()
2694 
2695             if names is not None:
2696                 if (self.usecols is not None and len(names) != len(self.usecols)) or (
2697                     self.usecols is None and len(names) != len(columns[0])
2698                 ):
2699                     raise ValueError(
2700                         "Number of passed names did not match "
2701                         "number of header fields in the file"
2702                     )
2703                 if len(columns) > 1:
2704                     raise TypeError("Cannot pass names with multi-index columns")
2705 
2706                 if self.usecols is not None:
2707                     # Set _use_cols. We don't store columns because they are
2708                     # overwritten.
2709                     self._handle_usecols(columns, names)
2710                 else:
2711                     self._col_indices = None
2712                     num_original_columns = len(names)
2713                 columns = [names]
2714             else:
2715                 columns = self._handle_usecols(columns, columns[0])
2716         else:
2717             try:
2718                 line = self._buffered_line()
2719 
2720             except StopIteration as err:
2721                 if not names:
2722                     raise EmptyDataError("No columns to parse from file") from err
2723 
2724                 line = names[:]
2725 
2726             ncols = len(line)
2727             num_original_columns = ncols
2728 
2729             if not names:
2730                 if self.prefix:
2731                     columns = [[f"{self.prefix}{i}" for i in range(ncols)]]
2732                 else:
2733                     columns = [list(range(ncols))]
2734                 columns = self._handle_usecols(columns, columns[0])
2735             else:
2736                 if self.usecols is None or len(names) >= num_original_columns:
2737                     columns = self._handle_usecols([names], names)
2738                     num_original_columns = len(names)
2739                 else:
2740                     if not callable(self.usecols) and len(names) != len(self.usecols):
2741                         raise ValueError(
2742                             "Number of passed names did not match number of "
2743                             "header fields in the file"
2744                         )
2745                     # Ignore output but set used columns.
2746                     self._handle_usecols([names], names)
2747                     columns = [names]
2748                     num_original_columns = ncols
2749 
2750         return columns, num_original_columns, unnamed_cols

2752     def _handle_usecols(self, columns, usecols_key):
2753         """
2754         Sets self._col_indices
2755 
2756         usecols_key is used if there are string usecols.
2757         """
2758         if self.usecols is not None:
2759             if callable(self.usecols):
2760                 col_indices = _evaluate_usecols(self.usecols, usecols_key)
2761             elif any(isinstance(u, str) for u in self.usecols):
2762                 if len(columns) > 1:
2763                     raise ValueError(
2764                         "If using multiple headers, usecols must be integers."
2765                     )
2766                 col_indices = []
2767 
2768                 for col in self.usecols:
2769                     if isinstance(col, str):
2770                         try:
2771                             col_indices.append(usecols_key.index(col))
2772                         except ValueError:
2773                             _validate_usecols_names(self.usecols, usecols_key)
2774                     else:
2775                         col_indices.append(col)
2776             else:
2777                 col_indices = self.usecols
2778 
2779             columns = [
2780                 [n for i, n in enumerate(column) if i in col_indices]
2781                 for column in columns
2782             ]
2783             self._col_indices = col_indices
2784         return columns

2786     def _buffered_line(self):
2787         """
2788         Return a line from buffer, filling buffer if required.
2789         """
2790         if len(self.buf) > 0:
2791             return self.buf[0]
2792         else:
2793             return self._next_line()

2795     def _check_for_bom(self, first_row):
2796         """
2797         Checks whether the file begins with the BOM character.
2798         If it does, remove it. In addition, if there is quoting
2799         in the field subsequent to the BOM, remove it as well
2800         because it technically takes place at the beginning of
2801         the name, not the middle of it.
2802         """
2803         # first_row will be a list, so we need to check
2804         # that that list is not empty before proceeding.
2805         if not first_row:
2806             return first_row
2807 
2808         # The first element of this row is the one that could have the
2809         # BOM that we want to remove. Check that the first element is a
2810         # string before proceeding.
2811         if not isinstance(first_row[0], str):
2812             return first_row
2813 
2814         # Check that the string is not empty, as that would
2815         # obviously not have a BOM at the start of it.
2816         if not first_row[0]:
2817             return first_row
2818 
2819         # Since the string is non-empty, check that it does
2820         # in fact begin with a BOM.
2821         first_elt = first_row[0][0]
2822         if first_elt != _BOM:
2823             return first_row
2824 
2825         first_row_bom = first_row[0]
2826 
2827         if len(first_row_bom) > 1 and first_row_bom[1] == self.quotechar:
2828             start = 2
2829             quote = first_row_bom[1]
2830             end = first_row_bom[2:].index(quote) + 2
2831 
2832             # Extract the data between the quotation marks
2833             new_row = first_row_bom[start:end]
2834 
2835             # Extract any remaining data after the second
2836             # quotation mark.
2837             if len(first_row_bom) > end + 1:
2838                 new_row += first_row_bom[end + 1 :]
2839             return [new_row] + first_row[1:]
2840 
2841         elif len(first_row_bom) > 1:
2842             return [first_row_bom[1:]]
2843         else:
2844             # First row is just the BOM, so we
2845             # return an empty string.
2846             return [""]
2847 
2848     def _is_line_empty(self, line):
2849         """
2850         Check if a line is empty or not.
2851 
2852         Parameters
2853         ----------
2854         line : str, array-like
2855             The line of data to check.
2856 
2857         Returns
2858         -------
2859         boolean : Whether or not the line is empty.
2860         """
2861         return not line or all(not x for x in line)

2863     def _next_line(self):
2864         if isinstance(self.data, list):
2865             while self.skipfunc(self.pos):
2866                 self.pos += 1
2867 
2868             while True:
2869                 try:
2870                     line = self._check_comments([self.data[self.pos]])[0]
2871                     self.pos += 1
2872                     # either uncommented or blank to begin with
2873                     if not self.skip_blank_lines and (
2874                         self._is_line_empty(self.data[self.pos - 1]) or line
2875                     ):
2876                         break
2877                     elif self.skip_blank_lines:
2878                         ret = self._remove_empty_lines([line])
2879                         if ret:
2880                             line = ret[0]
2881                             break
2882                 except IndexError:
2883                     raise StopIteration
2884         else:
2885             while self.skipfunc(self.pos):
2886                 self.pos += 1
2887                 next(self.data)
2888 
2889             while True:
2890                 orig_line = self._next_iter_line(row_num=self.pos + 1)
2891                 self.pos += 1
2892 
2893                 if orig_line is not None:
2894                     line = self._check_comments([orig_line])[0]
2895 
2896                     if self.skip_blank_lines:
2897                         ret = self._remove_empty_lines([line])
2898 
2899                         if ret:
2900                             line = ret[0]
2901                             break
2902                     elif self._is_line_empty(orig_line) or line:
2903                         break
2904 
2905         # This was the first line of the file,
2906         # which could contain the BOM at the
2907         # beginning of it.
2908         if self.pos == 1:
2909             line = self._check_for_bom(line)
2910 
2911         self.line_pos += 1
2912         self.buf.append(line)
2913         return line

2915     def _alert_malformed(self, msg, row_num):
2916         """
2917         Alert a user about a malformed row.
2918 
2919         If `self.error_bad_lines` is True, the alert will be `ParserError`.
2920         If `self.warn_bad_lines` is True, the alert will be printed out.
2921 
2922         Parameters
2923         ----------
2924         msg : The error message to display.
2925         row_num : The row number where the parsing error occurred.
2926                   Because this row number is displayed, we 1-index,
2927                   even though we 0-index internally.
2928         """
2929         if self.error_bad_lines:
2930             raise ParserError(msg)
2931         elif self.warn_bad_lines:
2932             base = f"Skipping line {row_num}: "
2933             sys.stderr.write(base + msg + "\n")
2934 
2935     def _next_iter_line(self, row_num):
2936         """
2937         Wrapper around iterating through `self.data` (CSV source).
2938 
2939         When a CSV error is raised, we check for specific
2940         error messages that allow us to customize the
2941         error message displayed to the user.
2942 
2943         Parameters
2944         ----------
2945         row_num : The row number of the line being parsed.
2946         """
2947         try:
2948             return next(self.data)
2949         except csv.Error as e:
2950             if self.warn_bad_lines or self.error_bad_lines:
2951                 msg = str(e)
2952 
2953                 if "NULL byte" in msg or "line contains NUL" in msg:
2954                     msg = (
2955                         "NULL byte detected. This byte "
2956                         "cannot be processed in Python's "
2957                         "native csv library at the moment, "
2958                         "so please pass in engine='c' instead"
2959                     )
2960 
2961                 if self.skipfooter > 0:
2962                     reason = (
2963                         "Error could possibly be due to "
2964                         "parsing errors in the skipped footer rows "
2965                         "(the skipfooter keyword is only applied "
2966                         "after Python's csv library has parsed "
2967                         "all rows)."
2968                     )
2969                     msg += ". " + reason
2970 
2971                 self._alert_malformed(msg, row_num)
2972             return None
2973 
2974     def _check_comments(self, lines):
2975         if self.comment is None:
2976             return lines
2977         ret = []
2978         for l in lines:
2979             rl = []
2980             for x in l:
2981                 if not isinstance(x, str) or self.comment not in x:
2982                     rl.append(x)
2983                 else:
2984                     x = x[: x.find(self.comment)]
2985                     if len(x) > 0:
2986                         rl.append(x)
2987                     break
2988             ret.append(rl)
2989         return ret

2991     def _remove_empty_lines(self, lines):
2992         """
2993         Iterate through the lines and remove any that are
2994         either empty or contain only one whitespace value
2995 
2996         Parameters
2997         ----------
2998         lines : array-like
2999             The array of lines that we are to filter.
3000 
3001         Returns
3002         -------
3003         filtered_lines : array-like
3004             The same array of lines with the "empty" ones removed.
3005         """
3006         ret = []
3007         for l in lines:
3008             # Remove empty lines and lines with only one whitespace value
3009             if (
3010                 len(l) > 1
3011                 or len(l) == 1
3012                 and (not isinstance(l[0], str) or l[0].strip())
3013             ):
3014                 ret.append(l)
3015         return ret

3025     def _search_replace_num_columns(self, lines, search, replace):
3026         ret = []
3027         for l in lines:
3028             rl = []
3029             for i, x in enumerate(l):
3030                 if (
3031                     not isinstance(x, str)
3032                     or search not in x
3033                     or (self._no_thousands_columns and i in self._no_thousands_columns)
3034                     or self.nonnum.search(x.strip())
3035                 ):
3036                     rl.append(x)
3037                 else:
3038                     rl.append(x.replace(search, replace))
3039             ret.append(rl)
3040         return ret

3055     def _get_index_name(self, columns):
3056         """
3057         Try several cases to get lines:
3058 
3059         0) There are headers on row 0 and row 1 and their
3060         total summed lengths equals the length of the next line.
3061         Treat row 0 as columns and row 1 as indices
3062         1) Look for implicit index: there are more columns
3063         on row 1 than row 0. If this is true, assume that row
3064         1 lists index columns and row 0 lists normal columns.
3065         2) Get index from the columns if it was listed.
3066         """
3067         orig_names = list(columns)
3068         columns = list(columns)
3069 
3070         try:
3071             line = self._next_line()
3072         except StopIteration:
3073             line = None
3074 
3075         try:
3076             next_line = self._next_line()
3077         except StopIteration:
3078             next_line = None
3079 
3080         # implicitly index_col=0 b/c 1 fewer column names
3081         implicit_first_cols = 0
3082         if line is not None:
3083             # leave it 0, #2442
3084             # Case 1
3085             if self.index_col is not False:
3086                 implicit_first_cols = len(line) - self.num_original_columns
3087 
3088             # Case 0
3089             if next_line is not None:
3090                 if len(next_line) == len(line) + self.num_original_columns:
3091                     # column and index names on diff rows
3092                     self.index_col = list(range(len(line)))
3093                     self.buf = self.buf[1:]
3094 
3095                     for c in reversed(line):
3096                         columns.insert(0, c)
3097 
3098                     # Update list of original names to include all indices.
3099                     orig_names = list(columns)
3100                     self.num_original_columns = len(columns)
3101                     return line, orig_names, columns
3102 
3103         if implicit_first_cols > 0:
3104             # Case 1
3105             self._implicit_index = True
3106             if self.index_col is None:
3107                 self.index_col = list(range(implicit_first_cols))
3108 
3109             index_name = None
3110 
3111         else:
3112             # Case 2
3113             (index_name, columns_, self.index_col) = _clean_index_names(
3114                 columns, self.index_col, self.unnamed_cols
3115             )
3116 
3117         return index_name, orig_names, columns

3119     def _rows_to_cols(self, content):
3120         col_len = self.num_original_columns
3121 
3122         if self._implicit_index:
3123             col_len += len(self.index_col)
3124 
3125         max_len = max(len(row) for row in content)
3126 
3127         # Check that there are no rows with too many
3128         # elements in their row (rows with too few
3129         # elements are padded with NaN).
3130         if max_len > col_len and self.index_col is not False and self.usecols is None:
3131 
3132             footers = self.skipfooter if self.skipfooter else 0
3133             bad_lines = []
3134 
3135             iter_content = enumerate(content)
3136             content_len = len(content)
3137             content = []
3138 
3139             for (i, l) in iter_content:
3140                 actual_len = len(l)
3141 
3142                 if actual_len > col_len:
3143                     if self.error_bad_lines or self.warn_bad_lines:
3144                         row_num = self.pos - (content_len - i + footers)
3145                         bad_lines.append((row_num, actual_len))
3146 
3147                         if self.error_bad_lines:
3148                             break
3149                 else:
3150                     content.append(l)
3151 
3152             for row_num, actual_len in bad_lines:
3153                 msg = (
3154                     f"Expected {col_len} fields in line {row_num + 1}, saw "
3155                     f"{actual_len}"
3156                 )
3157                 if (
3158                     self.delimiter
3159                     and len(self.delimiter) > 1
3160                     and self.quoting != csv.QUOTE_NONE
3161                 ):
3162                     # see gh-13374
3163                     reason = (
3164                         "Error could possibly be due to quotes being "
3165                         "ignored when a multi-char delimiter is used."
3166                     )
3167                     msg += ". " + reason
3168 
3169                 self._alert_malformed(msg, row_num + 1)
3170 
3171         # see gh-13320
3172         zipped_content = list(lib.to_object_array(content, min_width=col_len).T)
3173 
3174         if self.usecols:
3175             if self._implicit_index:
3176                 zipped_content = [
3177                     a
3178                     for i, a in enumerate(zipped_content)
3179                     if (
3180                         i < len(self.index_col)
3181                         or i - len(self.index_col) in self._col_indices
3182                     )
3183                 ]
3184             else:
3185                 zipped_content = [
3186                     a for i, a in enumerate(zipped_content) if i in self._col_indices
3187                 ]
3188         return zipped_content

3190     def _get_lines(self, rows=None):
3191         lines = self.buf
3192         new_rows = None
3193 
3194         # already fetched some number
3195         if rows is not None:
3196             # we already have the lines in the buffer
3197             if len(self.buf) >= rows:
3198                 new_rows, self.buf = self.buf[:rows], self.buf[rows:]
3199 
3200             # need some lines
3201             else:
3202                 rows -= len(self.buf)
3203 
3204         if new_rows is None:
3205             if isinstance(self.data, list):
3206                 if self.pos > len(self.data):
3207                     raise StopIteration
3208                 if rows is None:
3209                     new_rows = self.data[self.pos :]
3210                     new_pos = len(self.data)
3211                 else:
3212                     new_rows = self.data[self.pos : self.pos + rows]
3213                     new_pos = self.pos + rows
3214 
3215                 # Check for stop rows. n.b.: self.skiprows is a set.
3216                 if self.skiprows:
3217                     new_rows = [
3218                         row
3219                         for i, row in enumerate(new_rows)
3220                         if not self.skipfunc(i + self.pos)
3221                     ]
3222 
3223                 lines.extend(new_rows)
3224                 self.pos = new_pos
3225 
3226             else:
3227                 new_rows = []
3228                 try:
3229                     if rows is not None:
3230                         for _ in range(rows):
3231                             new_rows.append(next(self.data))
3232                         lines.extend(new_rows)
3233                     else:
3234                         rows = 0
3235 
3236                         while True:
3237                             new_row = self._next_iter_line(row_num=self.pos + rows + 1)
3238                             rows += 1
3239 
3240                             if new_row is not None:
3241                                 new_rows.append(new_row)
3242 
3243                 except StopIteration:
3244                     if self.skiprows:
3245                         new_rows = [
3246                             row
3247                             for i, row in enumerate(new_rows)
3248                             if not self.skipfunc(i + self.pos)
3249                         ]
3250                     lines.extend(new_rows)
3251                     if len(lines) == 0:
3252                         raise
3253                 self.pos += len(new_rows)
3254 
3255             self.buf = []
3256         else:
3257             lines = new_rows
3258 
3259         if self.skipfooter:
3260             lines = lines[: -self.skipfooter]
3261 
3262         lines = self._check_comments(lines)
3263         if self.skip_blank_lines:
3264             lines = self._remove_empty_lines(lines)
3265         lines = self._check_thousands(lines)
3266         return self._check_decimal(lines)

3269 def _make_date_converter(
3270     date_parser=None, dayfirst=False, infer_datetime_format=False, cache_dates=True
3271 ):
3272     def converter(*date_cols):
3273         if date_parser is None:
3274             strs = parsing.concat_date_cols(date_cols)
3275 
3276             try:
3277                 return tools.to_datetime(
3278                     ensure_object(strs),
3279                     utc=None,
3280                     dayfirst=dayfirst,
3281                     errors="ignore",
3282                     infer_datetime_format=infer_datetime_format,
3283                     cache=cache_dates,
3284                 ).to_numpy()
3285 
3286             except ValueError:
3287                 return tools.to_datetime(
3288                     parsing.try_parse_dates(strs, dayfirst=dayfirst), cache=cache_dates
3289                 )
3290         else:
3291             try:
3292                 result = tools.to_datetime(
3293                     date_parser(*date_cols), errors="ignore", cache=cache_dates
3294                 )
3295                 if isinstance(result, datetime.datetime):
3296                     raise Exception("scalar parser")
3297                 return result
3298             except Exception:
3299                 try:
3300                     return tools.to_datetime(
3301                         parsing.try_parse_dates(
3302                             parsing.concat_date_cols(date_cols),
3303                             parser=date_parser,
3304                             dayfirst=dayfirst,
3305                         ),
3306                         errors="ignore",
3307                     )
3308                 except Exception:
3309                     return generic_parser(date_parser, *date_cols)
3310 
3311     return converter

3314 def _process_date_conversion(
3315     data_dict,
3316     converter,
3317     parse_spec,
3318     index_col,
3319     index_names,
3320     columns,
3321     keep_date_col=False,
3322 ):
3323     def _isindex(colspec):
3324         return (isinstance(index_col, list) and colspec in index_col) or (
3325             isinstance(index_names, list) and colspec in index_names
3326         )
3327 
3328     new_cols = []
3329     new_data = {}
3330 
3331     orig_names = columns
3332     columns = list(columns)
3333 
3334     date_cols = set()
3335 
3336     if parse_spec is None or isinstance(parse_spec, bool):
3337         return data_dict, columns
3338 
3339     if isinstance(parse_spec, list):
3340         # list of column lists
3341         for colspec in parse_spec:
3342             if is_scalar(colspec):
3343                 if isinstance(colspec, int) and colspec not in data_dict:
3344                     colspec = orig_names[colspec]
3345                 if _isindex(colspec):
3346                     continue
3347                 data_dict[colspec] = converter(data_dict[colspec])
3348             else:
3349                 new_name, col, old_names = _try_convert_dates(
3350                     converter, colspec, data_dict, orig_names
3351                 )
3352                 if new_name in data_dict:
3353                     raise ValueError(f"New date column already in dict {new_name}")
3354                 new_data[new_name] = col
3355                 new_cols.append(new_name)
3356                 date_cols.update(old_names)
3357 
3358     elif isinstance(parse_spec, dict):
3359         # dict of new name to column list
3360         for new_name, colspec in parse_spec.items():
3361             if new_name in data_dict:
3362                 raise ValueError(f"Date column {new_name} already in dict")
3363 
3364             _, col, old_names = _try_convert_dates(
3365                 converter, colspec, data_dict, orig_names
3366             )
3367 
3368             new_data[new_name] = col
3369             new_cols.append(new_name)
3370             date_cols.update(old_names)
3371 
3372     data_dict.update(new_data)
3373     new_cols.extend(columns)
3374 
3375     if not keep_date_col:
3376         for c in list(date_cols):
3377             data_dict.pop(c)
3378             new_cols.remove(c)
3379 
3380     return data_dict, new_cols
3381 
3382 
3383 def _try_convert_dates(parser, colspec, data_dict, columns):
3384     colset = set(columns)
3385     colnames = []
3386 
3387     for c in colspec:
3388         if c in colset:
3389             colnames.append(c)
3390         elif isinstance(c, int) and c not in columns:
3391             colnames.append(columns[c])
3392         else:
3393             colnames.append(c)
3394 
3395     new_name = "_".join(str(x) for x in colnames)
3396     to_parse = [data_dict[c] for c in colnames if c in data_dict]
3397 
3398     new_col = parser(*to_parse)
3399     return new_name, new_col, colnames

3402 def _clean_na_values(na_values, keep_default_na=True):
3403 
3404     if na_values is None:
3405         if keep_default_na:
3406             na_values = STR_NA_VALUES
3407         else:
3408             na_values = set()
3409         na_fvalues = set()
3410     elif isinstance(na_values, dict):
3411         old_na_values = na_values.copy()
3412         na_values = {}  # Prevent aliasing.
3413 
3414         # Convert the values in the na_values dictionary
3415         # into array-likes for further use. This is also
3416         # where we append the default NaN values, provided
3417         # that `keep_default_na=True`.
3418         for k, v in old_na_values.items():
3419             if not is_list_like(v):
3420                 v = [v]
3421 
3422             if keep_default_na:
3423                 v = set(v) | STR_NA_VALUES
3424 
3425             na_values[k] = v
3426         na_fvalues = {k: _floatify_na_values(v) for k, v in na_values.items()}
3427     else:
3428         if not is_list_like(na_values):
3429             na_values = [na_values]
3430         na_values = _stringify_na_values(na_values)
3431         if keep_default_na:
3432             na_values = na_values | STR_NA_VALUES
3433 
3434         na_fvalues = _floatify_na_values(na_values)
3435 
3436     return na_values, na_fvalues

3439 def _clean_index_names(columns, index_col, unnamed_cols):
3440     if not _is_index_col(index_col):
3441         return None, columns, index_col
3442 
3443     columns = list(columns)
3444 
3445     cp_cols = list(columns)
3446     index_names = []
3447 
3448     # don't mutate
3449     index_col = list(index_col)
3450 
3451     for i, c in enumerate(index_col):
3452         if isinstance(c, str):
3453             index_names.append(c)
3454             for j, name in enumerate(cp_cols):
3455                 if name == c:
3456                     index_col[i] = j
3457                     columns.remove(name)
3458                     break
3459         else:
3460             name = cp_cols[c]
3461             columns.remove(name)
3462             index_names.append(name)
3463 
3464     # Only clean index names that were placeholders.
3465     for i, name in enumerate(index_names):
3466         if isinstance(name, str) and name in unnamed_cols:
3467             index_names[i] = None
3468 
3469     return index_names, columns, index_col

3472 def _get_empty_meta(columns, index_col, index_names, dtype=None):
3473     columns = list(columns)
3474 
3475     # Convert `dtype` to a defaultdict of some kind.
3476     # This will enable us to write `dtype[col_name]`
3477     # without worrying about KeyError issues later on.
3478     if not isinstance(dtype, dict):
3479         # if dtype == None, default will be np.object.
3480         default_dtype = dtype or np.object
3481         dtype = defaultdict(lambda: default_dtype)
3482     else:
3483         # Save a copy of the dictionary.
3484         _dtype = dtype.copy()
3485         dtype = defaultdict(lambda: np.object)
3486 
3487         # Convert column indexes to column names.
3488         for k, v in _dtype.items():
3489             col = columns[k] if is_integer(k) else k
3490             dtype[col] = v
3491 
3492     # Even though we have no data, the "index" of the empty DataFrame
3493     # could for example still be an empty MultiIndex. Thus, we need to
3494     # check whether we have any index columns specified, via either:
3495     #
3496     # 1) index_col (column indices)
3497     # 2) index_names (column names)
3498     #
3499     # Both must be non-null to ensure a successful construction. Otherwise,
3500     # we have to create a generic empty Index.
3501     if (index_col is None or index_col is False) or index_names is None:
3502         index = Index([])
3503     else:
3504         data = [Series([], dtype=dtype[name]) for name in index_names]
3505         index = ensure_index_from_sequences(data, names=index_names)
3506         index_col.sort()
3507 
3508         for i, n in enumerate(index_col):
3509             columns.pop(n - i)
3510 
3511     col_dict = {col_name: Series([], dtype=dtype[col_name]) for col_name in columns}
3512 
3513     return index, columns, col_dict

3516 def _floatify_na_values(na_values):
3517     # create float versions of the na_values
3518     result = set()
3519     for v in na_values:
3520         try:
3521             v = float(v)
3522             if not np.isnan(v):
3523                 result.add(v)
3524         except (TypeError, ValueError, OverflowError):
3525             pass
3526     return result
3527 
3528 
3529 def _stringify_na_values(na_values):
3530     """ return a stringified and numeric for these values """
3531     result = []
3532     for x in na_values:
3533         result.append(str(x))
3534         result.append(x)
3535         try:
3536             v = float(x)
3537 
3538             # we are like 999 here
3539             if v == int(v):
3540                 v = int(v)
3541                 result.append(f"{v}.0")
3542                 result.append(str(v))
3543 
3544             result.append(v)
3545         except (TypeError, ValueError, OverflowError):
3546             pass
3547         try:
3548             result.append(int(x))
3549         except (TypeError, ValueError, OverflowError):
3550             pass
3551     return set(result)

3554 def _get_na_values(col, na_values, na_fvalues, keep_default_na):
3555     """
3556     Get the NaN values for a given column.
3557 
3558     Parameters
3559     ----------
3560     col : str
3561         The name of the column.
3562     na_values : array-like, dict
3563         The object listing the NaN values as strings.
3564     na_fvalues : array-like, dict
3565         The object listing the NaN values as floats.
3566     keep_default_na : bool
3567         If `na_values` is a dict, and the column is not mapped in the
3568         dictionary, whether to return the default NaN values or the empty set.
3569 
3570     Returns
3571     -------
3572     nan_tuple : A length-two tuple composed of
3573 
3574         1) na_values : the string NaN values for that column.
3575         2) na_fvalues : the float NaN values for that column.
3576     """
3577     if isinstance(na_values, dict):
3578         if col in na_values:
3579             return na_values[col], na_fvalues[col]
3580         else:
3581             if keep_default_na:
3582                 return STR_NA_VALUES, set()
3583 
3584             return set(), set()
3585     else:
3586         return na_values, na_fvalues
3587

3589 def _get_col_names(colspec, columns):
3590     colset = set(columns)
3591     colnames = []
3592     for c in colspec:
3593         if c in colset:
3594             colnames.append(c)
3595         elif isinstance(c, int):
3596             colnames.append(columns[c])
3597     return colnames

3599 
3600 class FixedWidthReader(abc.Iterator):
3601     """
3602     A reader of fixed-width lines.
3603     """
3604 
3605     def __init__(self, f, colspecs, delimiter, comment, skiprows=None, infer_nrows=100):
3606         self.f = f
3607         self.buffer = None
3608         self.delimiter = "\r\n" + delimiter if delimiter else "\n\r\t "
3609         self.comment = comment
3610         if colspecs == "infer":
3611             self.colspecs = self.detect_colspecs(
3612                 infer_nrows=infer_nrows, skiprows=skiprows
3613             )
3614         else:
3615             self.colspecs = colspecs
3616 
3617         if not isinstance(self.colspecs, (tuple, list)):
3618             raise TypeError(
3619                 "column specifications must be a list or tuple, "
3620                 f"input was a {type(colspecs).__name__}"
3621             )
3622 
3623         for colspec in self.colspecs:
3624             if not (
3625                 isinstance(colspec, (tuple, list))
3626                 and len(colspec) == 2
3627                 and isinstance(colspec[0], (int, np.integer, type(None)))
3628                 and isinstance(colspec[1], (int, np.integer, type(None)))
3629             ):
3630                 raise TypeError(
3631                     "Each column specification must be "
3632                     "2 element tuple or list of integers"
3633                 )
3634 
3635     def get_rows(self, infer_nrows, skiprows=None):
3636         """
3637         Read rows from self.f, skipping as specified.
3638 
3639         We distinguish buffer_rows (the first <= infer_nrows
3640         lines) from the rows returned to detect_colspecs
3641         because it's simpler to leave the other locations
3642         with skiprows logic alone than to modify them to
3643         deal with the fact we skipped some rows here as
3644         well.
3645 
3646         Parameters
3647         ----------
3648         infer_nrows : int
3649             Number of rows to read from self.f, not counting
3650             rows that are skipped.
3651         skiprows: set, optional
3652             Indices of rows to skip.
3653 
3654         Returns
3655         -------
3656         detect_rows : list of str
3657             A list containing the rows to read.
3658 
3659         """
3660         if skiprows is None:
3661             skiprows = set()
3662         buffer_rows = []
3663         detect_rows = []
3664         for i, row in enumerate(self.f):
3665             if i not in skiprows:
3666                 detect_rows.append(row)
3667             buffer_rows.append(row)
3668             if len(detect_rows) >= infer_nrows:
3669                 break
3670         self.buffer = iter(buffer_rows)
3671         return detect_rows
3672 
3673     def detect_colspecs(self, infer_nrows=100, skiprows=None):
3674         # Regex escape the delimiters
3675         delimiters = "".join(fr"\{x}" for x in self.delimiter)
3676         pattern = re.compile(f"([^{delimiters}]+)")
3677         rows = self.get_rows(infer_nrows, skiprows)
3678         if not rows:
3679             raise EmptyDataError("No rows from which to infer column width")
3680         max_len = max(map(len, rows))
3681         mask = np.zeros(max_len + 1, dtype=int)
3682         if self.comment is not None:
3683             rows = [row.partition(self.comment)[0] for row in rows]
3684         for row in rows:
3685             for m in pattern.finditer(row):
3686                 mask[m.start() : m.end()] = 1
3687         shifted = np.roll(mask, 1)
3688         shifted[0] = 0
3689         edges = np.where((mask ^ shifted) == 1)[0]
3690         edge_pairs = list(zip(edges[::2], edges[1::2]))
3691         return edge_pairs
3692 
3693     def __next__(self):
3694         if self.buffer is not None:
3695             try:
3696                 line = next(self.buffer)
3697             except StopIteration:
3698                 self.buffer = None
3699                 line = next(self.f)
3700         else:
3701             line = next(self.f)
3702         # Note: 'colspecs' is a sequence of half-open intervals.
3703         return [line[fromm:to].strip(self.delimiter) for (fromm, to) in self.colspecs]
3704
